The Prague Stock Exchange plunges into the red towards the close of business.
After the steep drop in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions in ČEZ shares reached almost half of normal day-to-day business.
The Prague Stock Exchange continued Monday's slump right at the start of Tuesday trading, when it fell by another six percentage points.
This time, the reason for the slump was on Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, this reflects the market's reaction to the result of the vote by the US House of Representatives, which refused to support a stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Case of equities in Asia
Equities on the Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses during the day.
The index of the Hang Seng Stock Exchange in Hong Kong lost almost four percentage points during the course of the business day, but was later able to make up some of the losses, thus reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while markets in Shanghai were closed.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then reduced losses to 4.3 percent.
The stock market in Taiwan fell by 3.6 percent according to the index there.
"The timing of the US bailout is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide," said Joseph Yam, head of Hong Kong's monetary authority.
Hong Kong, although it belongs to China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, American lawmakers should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and pass the bill to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries would also be affected by the slump.
A bloodbath of American stocks
The US House of Representatives on Monday rejected the plan to support the financial system, for which up to 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion CZK) should be spent.
Lawmakers ignored President George Bush's call to support the plan.
In Bush's view, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
American stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, with major stock indices posting their biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index fell by almost seven percent, a similar slump it had last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but as soon as there were signs that the bill would not pass in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress makes concession: US government is allowed to pump 700 billion dollars into the banks
The top representatives of the US Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement on financial assistance to the US financial system.
This is due to be voted on early next week.
American lawmakers achieved a breakthrough in talks to adopt a bailout plan in the form of $700 billion (about 12 trillion crowns) of financial assistance to the American financial system.
However, this does not mean victory.
Members of Congress still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the US Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
According to various sources, the Senate could probably vote on the plan on Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, a notification that the plan will be adopted should be the first significant psychological factor for a revival of financial markets.
After that, however, there is a "disillusionment" due to the complicated mechanisms of how to help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a package to stabilize the market should look like," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, there could be a final vote on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislators met on Sunday night with the US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for the purchase of unsaleable mortgage assets from the financial companies, which plunge the financial firms into heavy losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must be effective in the market.
You have to continue the recovery plan, but I think we're there," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement in Congress before Sunday.
This is to reassure investors before doing business in Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone where a congressional decision could affect business on Monday.
So far, however, it is not entirely clear when both chambers of the US Congress will vote on the law, and there is also uncertainty as to whether the negotiations could fail at the last minute due to a problem.
Lawmakers hope it will be passed in the next few days.
The law, however, will undergo some changes.
The total amount earmarked for assistance to the system will be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion should be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
But Congress can block the distribution of the remaining money if it feels that the program is not doing its job, with another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush assesses progress in negotiations positively
The president has a veto over this decision, but Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program remains, which was based on obtaining finance to buy bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
"We worked everything out.
The House should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate should be able to vote on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President Bush was also satisfied with the progress.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and "appreciated the mutual effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the lead negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, completing perks and a timeline for funding the plan.
The new law is also intended to restrict the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies involved in the program and establishes a committee to supervise the fund.
This is to be headed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We've worked very this and made a lot of progress toward an agreement that works and is important to the market and to all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also anticipates help for homeowners who are struggling to repay their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new installments on mortgages it buys, with the goal of reducing monthly costs for debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"This is because we do not know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be bought.
This will be crucial to how the financial sector and the government share the losses among themselves," Marek told iHNed.cz server this week.
In Marek's view, whether the plan is adopted now or early next week is not decisive.
"It is much more important that congressmen agree to support the plan and that they pass it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement to adopt it is the most important thing at this moment," Marek emphasized.
Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, with a total of 29 percent
According to the first preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections on Sunday in Austria brought about a noticeable weakening of both parties of the previous grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly heavy losses, where the position of the previous chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously hanging in the balance.
In contrast, the returning officer of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthian Governor Jörg Haider, is preparing for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, the Social Democrats (SPÖ) remain the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, but compared to the last elections in 2006 it loses 5.5 percent of the vote.
The ÖVP fared even worse, losing almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in Austrian post-war history, and especially in the case of the People's Party, which called for early elections, this is a truly catastrophic result.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a clear lead over the SPÖ.
Voters, however, probably punished the party for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there was speculation about a possible resignation of the party chairman and former Vice-Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could be the case as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party's executive committee.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the election debacle, i.e. to a renewal of the grand coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP.
In view of the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) provisionally received 18 percent, the BZÖ eleven percent of the vote - the Social Democrats at the same time expressed their fear that the year 1999 could be repeated, when the People's Party had reached agreements with the populists (at that time the FPÖ was still united, in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) regarding a joint government.  which had even provoked sanctions from the European Union.
Jörg Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to cooperate with any party and expects a return to Austrian federal politics, is obviously counting on this development.
The Green Party also entered parliament, but suffered slight losses and slipped from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the four percent hurdle and therefore did not enter parliament.
Duel on a knife's edge: MP3 players against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost any phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls yet.
Therefore, of course, it looks like it's better to just buy yourself a phone.
Nevertheless, there are plenty of reasons why you should get an independent player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the requirements of the future owner.
Surely you hardly buy a great expensive record player for your home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
For once, such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for it.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on your shelf, you probably dream of at least one.
This is also the case with music when travelling, i.e. with compressed music, to put it simply - music in MP3 format.
Again, there are price and quality categories.
For some, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on one player, but just as a Pink Floyd fan will hardly be able to cope with headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide.
The service life of the batteries is also crucial.
Some good music players can do much more than just play music, but they can't even begin to do what mobile phones can do.
No modern device can be used as universally as the telephone.
In addition to the primary functions, making phone calls and texting, it can play music and videos, record both, it has sometimes a better, sometimes a worse camera and may also be able to navigate.
And if you include the smartphones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can take pictures.
But the universality of mobile phones also has disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you'll need to reload it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy guzzlers.
Only a few mobile phones can play music for more than ten-twelve hours, usually it is much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
That's why you should expect cheap phones to not be able to play music for more than a few hours.
If you then make phone calls from time to time, you prefer to buy a charger for the office - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players you will not have this problem, even the less good ones can withstand at least 9 hours of continuous operation with a single charge.
Another problem exists if you want to transfer the music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices has a USB lock, and not every mobile phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can transfer the music directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers can cope with the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones without reduction.
With players, you do not need any special software with exceptions (iPod).
You only need to feed the device with music from your PC via USB port.
Most mobile phones and players create a music library themselves, sorted by the name of the artist, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the rating by users.
Some devices only map the tree structure of the address directory, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When choosing a specific device, you should inquire in particular about the life of the battery, the storage capacity, the quality and type of sound and, of course, the ease of use.
If music is the main backdrop for you and you only hear it briefly every day, for example in the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is sufficient.
What almost every mobile phone can do.
You also don't have to control much what music formats a phone or player can handle.
MP3 can be done by everyone, and most of the music you get will be in this format right now.
The format is one of the most widely used, and besides, most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better phones also allow you to buy music online.
All you have to do is go to the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile Internet and you can buy a song or album.
This service in and of itself can be a compelling argument for why you should buy a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is bad and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are also not the lowest.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of selling music (be it via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their mobile phones with them.
If you feel like listening to something, reach for the phone in your jacket pocket while the player is forgotten at home.
However, it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free kit with you.
If not, you can resort to the built-in speaker that almost every phone has, but only very few MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music phones for many will be the price.
The cheapest usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you can get a decent Walkman.
The biggest handicap for most will be that there are no normal headphones.
The best and most technically sophisticated phones with a 3.5 mm opening for ordinary headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players lies in the ease of use.
The simplest - and not necessarily cheapest (see selection) - players can really be operated by anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the formerly normal cassette recorder or, for example, the record player is obvious.
There is no threat of a collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile Internet and a subsequent horrendous bill for data transmissions.
Which device should you reach for now?
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for removable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns are enough.
But beware.
The base models typically only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can also read 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, then grab Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
If you are one of the more demanding handsets, it is better to take specialized mobile phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have standalone control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use comes close to that of a single MP3 player.
The furthest along here is Sony Ericsson, whose mobile phones from the Walkman series have the same user interface as the MP3 players sold individually.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours) will afford you MP3 players from the above manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Perhaps
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, Czech operators offer practically all services as offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic ones to lower prices.
Perhaps this will not be long in coming.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that Czech mobile phone providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
Incidentally, this was also confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority ČTÚ, which drew attention to the fact that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the latest steps taken by the European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really makes a declaration of war.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that there is a lot of competition on the Czech market.
The chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, who has often said in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic, often agrees.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has many chances (by the way, he would probably hardly find frequencies anymore).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile phone market brought with it a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile phone providers had to react.
Even before the entry of companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market in Great Britain, there were similar voices as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don't have to look far for examples.
In February we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers, becoming the fifth largest provider in the country.
Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can concentrate on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a classic provider.
You do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually distinguish themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone calls and SMS, but this is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be quite a good move to bet on a non-clichéd target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking – the provider they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also gain a foothold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of service provision."
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile phone providers
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"Although we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking is more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region," Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile phone providers in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can to avoid creating a potential competitor.
Its interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has long been demonstrated by the GTS Novera group, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the corporate customer sector.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them," said Pavel Kaidl, the group's spokesperson.
Perhaps better times are coming.
According to unofficial information, the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this has been surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has great specifics compared to other markets.
So far, no subject with a complex and serious project in this field has approached us," says Vlastimil Sršeň from Telefónica O2's press department in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other providers also point out the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2's statement: "So far, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build on."
And she adds: "By the end of the year, hardly any virtual providers will appear in T-Mobile's network.
At this moment, we would have to have a concrete offer in order to be able to think so quickly."
Vodafone is more focused on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is precisely what we consider best from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for high-speed mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The approach of the mobile phone providers is easy to understand, another provider would mean more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decline in profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to something is also proven by the long back and forth about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ came from T-Mobile at the time when U:fon came onto the market.
This is also proven by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
Now, however, U:fon is a suitable argument why a virtual provider should not be allowed.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new entrant would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
In view of this approach of mobile operators, however, the absolute lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not only the attitude of the ČTÚ, which unfortunately - unlike Great Britain and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, took its very typical attitude to this entire problem.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile operator would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual provider for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," said Kristián Chalupa from the External Relations Department of the ÚOHS in response to our request.
From representatives of the providers, such a formulation would not be surprising.
This is more than worrying from an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, ensures that no one abuses its position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual providers work normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile phone services."
However, pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a reduction in prices are probably not in the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is really shocking about this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile phone providers, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same price of gasoline at the gas stations is certainly just a coincidence and the result of fierce competition.
"The Authority has not found any evidence in this case indicating anti-competitive action and therefore has no reason to intervene in the matter in any way.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so he does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for his actions on the market.
The necessary tools to open up the mobile market to virtual providers are also likely to be lacking for the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position in such a market.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different perspective - the market entry of a virtual provider always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile phone provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a certain segment.
But even if you don't go along with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile phone providers are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when negotiating with all suppliers.
The shifting of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a rather common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to extend the competences of the ČTÚ to the field of economic competition in telecommunications in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, although a number of experts had hoped that this would improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's possible when no one is looking
What remains unnoticed is the functioning of some pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but these are only partly public.
Usually, these are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile telephone services are offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach selected ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will then receive special price quotes (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which may lead to a termination of cooperation with the company concerned," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not get around among those responsible for the mobile phone providers.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, there can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
Indeed, they derive non-negligible profits from the activities of these companies, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are used by only a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it like the normal customers of the mobile operators."
But that alone should at least seem strange to the ČTÚ.
In addition, another question opens up for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such an approach, why do they oppose a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong powers to detect such activities and, if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration of the providers that they do not know about it and that their terms and conditions prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As the text has already pointed out several times, the entry of virtual providers has led to a significant fall in the price of the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence more or less in practice.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that the regulatory bodies intervened, not trying to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they managed to create the first virtual operator, and others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in competences is more than favourable in these cases.
But let us not throw in the towel.
If the background information is right and a virtual provider emerges soon, the Czech mobile market may soon start moving again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will not remain idle when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally no longer make more expensive phone calls than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem Where is my homeland in a ceremony on the occasion of the Day of Czech Statehood.
The anthem was re-recorded by the Orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo vocals, in choral version and in an instrumental version.
The vocal version was performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The arrangers of the anthem versions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the server iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national song is one of the most beautiful anthems.
He had previously told Czech Radio that he had chosen singers with young, representative voices who are distinctive and popular for the solo variants.
"From the very beginning, I tried to keep a clear diction with both and then also with the choir, so that the text is well understood, so that a harmony is created," says the conductor.
The Czech national anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was first performed in 1834 on the stage of the Estates Theatre in the originally Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music was by František Škroup.
It became popular, and people spontaneously adopted it.
The first verse of the song became an organic part of the national anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
