On Wednesday, the Prague public transport company will also transport on a chip for the first time
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will go down in the history of Prague Public Transport as a date when the first passengers board a metro, tram or bus carrying an electronic coupon in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
Currently, about one hundred thousand people who have the Opencard chip card can buy it.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, a 90-day or an annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it loaded onto their chip card at the same time at the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Since yesterday, the coupons are also available on the Internet on the pages of the transport company www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use internet sales can really forget about the output window in the metro stations, where they used to have to wait regularly in long lines for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon via the Internet, which is uploaded to the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points, travellers also have access to a counter with trained staff who advise interested parties when buying online and also put the coupon on the card," says project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, you can also upload the electronic coupons to the Opencard at self-service machines, which are mounted in some subway vestibules.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket validators, passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný adds.
The coupon is checked by a vending machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines, which will work from tomorrow, is simple.
All you have to do is insert the chip card and the previously purchased coupon will play itself.
The electronic coupons will be valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
In other words, in suburban trains and on bus lines numbered 300 to 499, with which mainly residents from municipalities of the Central Bohemian region can reach the capital.
"In the trains that are part of Prague's integrated transport, the train attendants have readers with which they can check the validity period of the coupons according to time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid the ticket control. This organization compiles the timetables for the Prague Public Transport Company.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver's cash register.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be presented to the driver, but the Opencard must also be placed in a marked place on the side of the cash register.
In this way, the driver checks the validity of the coupons that have been uploaded.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons displayed, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information," says Drápal.
A passenger who does not travel on suburban buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon ends can in turn go to the self-service machines, where the coupons are loaded onto the card.
Here, the information about the validity of his documents is displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the USA
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans had requested the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States.
This emerges from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would at least like to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans are said to have approached the US president with such a wish.
This can be seen, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
In the letter, the Germans of Český Krumlov ask the American president not to allow the return to Czechoslovakia of the "Sudetengau" - which was captured by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," reads a letter signed with the words "People who care about the fate of the Sudetes."
Since the annexation to Czechoslovakia leads the Sudeten Germans - knowing the Czech national character - to suspect that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to assume the patronage of the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the views of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you attribute this territory to a foreign state that oppresses and tries to eliminate minorities and has contributed absolutely nothing to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of revenge by the "Czech oppressors".
If the U.S. president had doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he initiated a referendum in the Bohemian Forest Gau on whether the inhabitants wanted to become part of the USA or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naïve in today's knowledge of post-war history, according to some contemporary witnesses it paints a good picture of the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Even if the Bohemian Germans at least had to suspect that their deportation from the republic would be negotiated, only a few of them even admitted such a possibility.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Still others believed they could just stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from České Budějovice.
He served in the war as a Budweiser German in the navy on the Baltic Sea.
When he was taken prisoner by the British at the end of the war and taken to a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, Czech would suit them," says Chalupa.
In his opinion, none of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected that he would be expelled from the republic on the basis of the Beneš decrees.
If you don't think - then pay!
An emotionally charged campaign aimed at motorists
Most expensive road safety action in Czech history.
This could also characterize the emotionally charged media campaign that the Ministry of Transport wants to start on Wednesday.
The authority of Minister Aleš Řebíček hopes that this will dissuade drivers from dangerous behaviour behind the wheel.
The campaign for 150 million crowns will run on television, radio, cinema, the Internet, but also on flyers.
It is intended to dissuade drivers from driving too fast and drinking and driving.
And also remind them to fasten their seat belts before starting their journey.
The campaign aims above all to appeal to young drivers, motorcyclists, pedestrians and, last but not least, professional drivers.
And what is shown in the spots?
Especially stories of people who appeal to emotions.
This is also evidenced by the "bloody" slogan of the whole campaign:
If you don't think - then pay!
The words "don't think" are written in capital letters on a license plate.
And in a pool of blood is the word "pay".
This means that you can pay for a moment of inattention with your own life.
The spots will "shock" viewers until 2010.
The ministry was inspired by similar campaigns in Anglo-Saxon countries, where you can normally see images with graphic shots of accident victims.
It is hoped that this will reduce the number of accidents and the number of traffic fatalities on Czech roads.
The spots were compiled by the agency Euro RSCG.
Carrot and stick for motorists
"For the drivers, the motto is carrot and stick.
Carrot means that when they drive on red, for example, they save time.
The whip is then the threat of punishment or accident.
The driver must be reminded of the risk," says Martin Kořán, a traffic psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
And that's why information campaigns in the press and, above all, negative advertising are necessary, says the psychologist.
In his opinion, signs that alert drivers to a danger are already less effective.
"If you put up a static board that warns of a danger, it will probably soon merge with the environment, and the drivers will no longer notice it," says Kořán.
Olmert would return almost all occupied territories in exchange for peace
The head of the provisional Israeli government, Ehud Olmert, has spoken out in favour of the return of virtually all territories occupied in 1967, including the Jordan Strip, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
