Questions after the accident: Are stewards on the bus illegal?
The law does not know them, in a long-distance coach walking around is not allowed
In connection with the tragic accident of a Student Agency bus near Padua, Italy, the question arises as to whether stewards and passengers are allowed to walk back and forth on the bus while driving.
"If we wanted to strictly and formally comply with the law, the activity of a steward is contrary to the law on road traffic," said Karel Hanzelka, spokesman for the Ministry of Transport.
The accident that killed a twenty-two-year-old stewardess last week was likely caused by the driver of the truck crossing the bus's path.
To make matters worse, the young woman was sitting next to the driver at that moment, in the least safe place in the car, although she still had two more seats available.
However, a bus can also have an accident or brake sharply at the moment when the steward delivers coffee or newspapers.
It also plays a role whether the bus is also equipped with standing room according to the vehicle registration document.
If this is not provided for on the bus, passengers must be seated.
Student Agency's long-distance coaches have no standing room; which the director of the company, Radim Jančura, confirmed to Aktuálně.cz.
"We discussed this with the ministry and this initially did not agree to the movement of travellers.
Later, this was withdrawn and we reached a consensus that passengers should be allowed to go to the toilet while driving if they are seated," he said.
The law knows no steward
"There is no clear legal interpretation for the role of a steward – no legislation describes this role.
However, there is also no legal provision prohibiting the carrier from providing services.
The Road Traffic Act recognises only the term vehicle attendant; However, it does not define its rights and obligations," the ministry spokesman Hanzelka clearly adds.
Josef Pokorný, Director of the Road Vehicles Department of the Ministry of Transport, believes that the law covers this issue retrospectively.
"It depends on whether the bus also has standing room in the product approval.
That's all," he emphasizes.
Buses are divided into city buses, where there is standing room and the speed limit is limited, commuter buses with standing room and a higher speed allowed, and long-distance coaches without standing room with the highest permitted speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
Like in an airplane, says the expert
BESIP expert for road safety Jaroslav Hořín does not see the movement of stewards on board a bus as a fundamental problem.
"With a smooth driving style, there are not many dangers, the situation is comparable to the service on board an aircraft.
Again, it's not certain when turbulence will come, and the stewardess can bump her head."
"However, if a bus brakes sharply, then of course the laws of physics also apply.
Just like in a city bus or in a tram.
The safety of the stewards must be clarified by the carrier through internal regulations," he says, adding that this problem is not completely solved from the point of view of the law.
Jančura is ready to cancel services
Student Agency is the only bus company offering stewards' services.
The company employs about two hundred people in this function.
The director does not consider her profession to be risky even after the accident.
"But as soon as I get the impression that the profession of steward is risky, I will delete it.
Passengers can receive coffee and newspapers when boarding.
That would also reduce costs," he says.
As an interest in safety, the director of Asiana Alexei Litvin justifies the lack of stewards in his buses. However, his company operates only a fraction of lines compared to Student Agency.
"We don't have stewardesses, we have been resisting this from the very beginning.
Sooner or later this ends with some fatal accident," he had said for Týden.cz less than a year ago.
It was an incredible tragedy
In the accident of a bus to Naples, a young stewardess from the Pilsen region, who had worked for the company for two years, had an accident.
The Slovenian truck had probably turned off the hard shoulder without flashing and had blocked the bus's journey.
The driver of the bus tried to evade by a sharp maneuver, but collided with the right front part with the truck.
Jančura denies that the two seats for the stewards were sold.
"These seats cannot be reserved for long-distance connections, they are blocked."
Company wants to sue truck drivers.
With compensation for the family of the young woman, the agency will not wait for the court ruling, but it also expects financial damages from the guilty.
A change in the law?
Not in sight
A more precise regulation of the movement of stewards on board a bus could bring a legal regulation, on which a thirty-member team of experts from the Ministry of Transport has been working for over a year.
"This, however, has not yet come to a concrete conclusion.
Buses are also not necessarily on the agenda, but rather the points system, the maximum speed on the motorway and the use of mobile phones when driving," says Hořín.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of stewards as something that could significantly endanger the safety of passengers," Hanzelka said, with the control of the safety of the buses being the responsibility of the police and the health and safety authorities.
A Czech judges the struggle for the seabed
He approaches an electronic map showing Australia and the adjacent sea areas.
However, he is not interested in the continent, but in a small dot, lost in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia and together with it the adjacent seabed.
The area is as large as the continent itself," says Italian lawyer Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the thirty-strong team of the UN Division for Oceans and the Rights of the Sea.
His boss, the division director, the Czech lawyer Václav Mikulka, follows the interpretation and supplements it.
There is enthusiasm and enthusiasm here.
So far, the seabed contains a little-known world rich in natural springs.
Here you can find petroleum, ore and other non-renewable raw materials, but also previously unknown living organisms, which, for example, hold the key to the development of a drug against cancer.
A seabed larger than the mainland
The riparian states today vehemently announced their claim to the new sea areas.
According to a UN convention, they are exercising their rights, which they agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay in Jamaica.
It is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends up to a few hundred kilometers from the shore of a country into the sea.
According to the Convention, this country has an exclusive claim to all sources of the continental shelf.
"Put simply, the continental shelf is considered to be the part of the seabed and its bottoms that is a natural continuation of the continent below the sea surface.
It crosses the borders of the shore sea, often also the limit of two hundred nautical miles of the so-called exclusive economic zone," explains Mikulka.
The request submitted by the country concerned to the Commission for the determination of the external borders of the continental shelf must be substantiated by extensive scientific and technical documentation based on many costly studies and measurements.
It is the result of many years of preparatory work.
"One of our tasks is to provide legal and technical support to the Commission.
The Commission has so far negotiated five applications from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the latter three countries have been successful," Mikulka adds.
The success of Australia, which was the first country to significantly expand its sea areas, recently met with an international response.
But New Zealand is also a winner - the extent of the seabed granted to it by the Commission last week is about 1.6 million square kilometres, about six times the size of the state proper.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in the investigations.
The benefits they will derive from the use of the seabed in the future will, they hope, be invaluable.
Other countries will also submit their applications gradually.
They can do so for ten years from the moment they ratify the Montego Bay Agreement.
Where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, which the Convention calls the "common heritage of mankind".
Here, no state has a special position.
The right to promote in this area is granted by an international institution established by the Convention.
"But the seabed is not a gold rush country," says director Mikulka with some exaggeration, adding that its "individual areas are legally precisely defined and the system is contractually anchored."
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed now also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern Bloc within the framework of the joint organization "Interoceanmetal".
In 1991, the Convention, like the investors of a few other countries, granted the status of a so-called "groundbreaking investor".
The organization has the right to mine in the ClarionClipperton Zone in the Pacific Ocean between Mexico, Hawaii and Kiribati.
The area to be investigated by the investor is slightly larger than the former Czechoslovakia.
The seabed is divided there, it is a kind of Tatras on the seabed.
"You can mine there on a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area is a rich site of polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese," said another lawyer, India's Pakshi Rajan.
