Now that the state elections in Bavaria are over, the first thing that could be a connection between BayernLB and Landesbank Baden-Württemberg could come closer.
This is not necessarily good news for Helaba.
Should the pressure for further mergers increase, it will gradually run out of partners.
In the south, it would only be a junior partner, although it has so far weathered the financial crisis far better than the houses in Munich and Stuttgart.
At the beginning of the year, the Sparkassen- und Giroverband Hessen-Thüringen, which holds an 85 percent stake in Helaba, put a stop to a merger with West LB.
At most, Nord LB would remain.
However, such geostrategic considerations are only one aspect.
On the other hand, it is about the question of how the different business models of the individual houses fit together.
In June, Merl said that the decisive question of which business model should ensure the future viability of the Landesbanken had not yet been answered by the German Savings Banks Association.
In the end, there could also be a dismantling of West LB, which, of course, is not desired there.
Thus, in the letter of the local board of directors, it is said that in any case a "total solution" for the house will be sought.
It remains to be seen how this can be reconciled with the merger of individual units with Deka-Bank.
The second Wiesn weekend is known as the "Italian weekend"
