Sleepless nights for creditors of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, stressed German Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück just last week.
How good that the politician used the word "relative" and also flew in that the German banking sector would not be spared from the crisis-ridden developments.
Because that happened at the weekend.
The Dax-listed Munich-based real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE) has received a billion-euro loan from a consortium of German banks to shield itself from the turbulence on the markets.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that loan assistance amounted to up to 35 billion euros.
Hypo Real Estate only has to pay interest on the part that it actually uses.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
This is due to losses at the subsidiary Depfa.
According to a newspaper report, the state financier had refinanced itself at extremely short notice for long-term projects for which it had lent money - which is no longer possible due to mistrust in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the Bank's cash reserve shrank by 95 percent to EUR 2.37 million, and the equity ratio had also fallen slightly from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
Current income and net income from financial transactions had fallen to zero compared to the same period of the previous year, while income from write-ups of receivables and certain securities as well as from the reversal of provisions in the lending business fell by more than 70 percent to EUR 5 million.
Only thanks to higher income from reimbursements of downstream transfer costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa Group as well as from the reimbursement of interest under the German Tax Code and from the management of Group companies, the decline in earnings was still moderate at around 16 percent.
After its privatisation in 1990, the former state financier initially speculated on commercial real estate loans, which were then spun off into Aareal Bank.
Because it earned too little in traditional state financing, Depfa then became increasingly involved in infrastructure projects and the financing of joint projects of private investors and the state (private-public partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the subsidiary, Hypo Real Estate must now make write-downs, which will have a "significant material effect" on the profit and loss account of the group, it is said quite vaguely.
The fact is that the dividend has been cancelled.
It had already been cut by two-thirds for 2007.
Since the takeover of Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a major provider of state and infrastructure finance.
It is more dependent than other institutions on funding in the interbank market because it has no customer deposits.
With the collapse of the American investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, lending among banks has largely dried up again as banks hoard their liquidity.
Every year, Hypo Real Estate needs short-term funds for refinancing part of Depfa's loan portfolio - around EUR 50 billion.
According to Hypo Real Estate, the Group's financing needs are covered by the loan for the foreseeable future and the company is "shielded from the influence of the currently largely dysfunctional international money markets".
According to other sources, the funds have secured refinancing until the end of 2009.
HRE CEO Georg Funke explained that Hypo Real Estate Group would no longer have to make use of the money markets in the foreseeable future.
The Bundesbank and the Federal Financial Supervisory Authority (BaFin) assume that the marketability of the Hypo Real Estate Group is now secured.
This is to be hoped for shareholders and creditors of the bank.
But given the dynamics and uncertainties of the crisis, there is probably no certainty.
It is even not unthinkable that the financing does not have to be used in full.
But even the opposite cannot be ruled out.
After late Sunday evening, according to reports, the bank was still on the verge of insolvency, even the at least temporary rescue cannot calm the minds.
The share price collapses by 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are holding up quite well.
While senior debt hardly moved, the prices of subordinated bonds are falling more significantly.
This mainly affects the bonds of the former subsidiary Württemberg Hypo and, understandably, the maturities beyond 2009.
If hypo real estate bonds previously appeared to be a speculative investment alternative, their intrinsic value must be regarded as dependent on the stability of the international financial system after the significant intensification of the banking crisis and the institution itself, which had brought the crisis into its house with the takeover of Depfa.
As long as the central banks, governments and less troubled commercial banks are still willing to support the system, it can be assumed that pensions will be repaid on time.
Or it will happen what hardly anyone dares to hope for at the moment - that the financial crisis will be overcome in the next 15 months.
