Rats also have feelings
A rat or a cockroach flees in case of danger does that mean that it also feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
But how could you check if they feel the same if they behave similarly to us?
In the Internet magazine "Edge" contributions of famous scientists have been published for several years.
In a series, SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you believe to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove this when we can't even prove that other people are conscious.
But in this case, we can at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and raise questions of sensation or consciousness in general, we enter rough terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as many other animals: it pretends to be dead, flees, or attacks.
People behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe in that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
For one, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more highly developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
So, at least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that humans are even different from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since so much of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness does not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so animal consciousness, whatever it may be, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness might look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, its exploration presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
One could study the consciousness processes of animals regardless of their contents, and this is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially using visualization as an example.
But this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick pursued, focuses on the neural correlates of consciousness rather than the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What is the result for the sensations?
I attribute it to the fact that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So, what we call "fear" is the mental state we are in when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies memory.
In this sense, sensations are closely tied to the regions of the cortex that distinguish primates and humans in particular.
Connected with linguistic nature, there are subtle gradations of feeling, because with the help of words and grammar we can differentiate and categorize states in order to attribute them to others as well as ourselves.
Antonio Damasio, on the other hand, thinks that sensations arise from more primitive activities in the body-feeling regions of the cortex and brainstem, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could well be involved in cross-genus sensations.
Theoretically, I cannot disagree with this, but I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans probably feels the same in both cases: But how can you check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach flees in case of danger whether it also feels fear?
In my opinion, mere behavioral similarity cannot yet prove equality of experience.
Although the neural comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain strains, cockroaches, on the other hand, do not even have a brain.
But is the brainstem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove this for humans, how could you prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to study the emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress at the neural level beckons, as long as the same is measured in rats and humans.
Just as I do not study language and consciousness in rats, nor sensations, I do not know if they exist.
You might think that's short-sighted, but I'd rather move forward than constantly run into a wall.
I'm just a practical emotionalist.
