For years, a mysterious phenomenon has been causing confusion among scientists - the swing-by anomaly.
The swing-by is a flight maneuver of space probes, in which they receive additional momentum in the gravitational field of a celestial body, such as the Earth.
As a result, the probes can save a lot of fuel.
The European-American Cassini-Huygens research probe used this physical trick, as did the Ulysses solar probe.
What has surprised the researchers for years, however, is that the missiles do not behave 100 percent as one would expect according to the time-honored law of gravity.
Rather, there are irregularities in speed.
The probes unexpectedly become faster or slower.
So far, physicists have not been able to explain this effect.
They christened it Swing-by-Anomaly.
Some experts fear that even Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity, which describes the gravitational pull of matter through a curvature of space, may not be entirely correct.
The American physicist Stephen Adler of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton still firmly believes that Einstein was not wrong, and tries to explain the swing-by anomaly using the so-called dark matter that astronomers have identified in the universe.
"Responsible for the anomaly could be dark matter, which could also be very close to Earth," he writes.
Space researchers have only known about the existence of dark matter for about ten years.
It obviously emanates an attraction whose effect on other celestial bodies can be observed.
It itself, on the other hand, is completely invisible, i.e. it does not send or reflect any electromagnetic radiation, especially no visible light.
According to the scientists' calculations, dark matter accounts for a good fifth of the total mass of the universe.
