Even worse is the fact that it is very unlikely that the matter would have ended up in court if it had not done so."
He added: "I note the impact that her act has had on her daughter over the years, according to Stephanie's father and mother's description.
Otherwise, she would clearly have been a promising, successful and happy young woman."
Official responsible for lost data is charged
The BBC has learned that the cabinet official, who lost highly confidential documents on a train in June, will be charged under the Public Security Act.
The man was seconded from the Department of Defence when he lost two highly confidential documents on a train to Waterloo.
The documents were handed over to the BBC before being handed over to the police.
It is the weakest charge within the law and there is no evidence of criminal intent.
BBC defence correspondent Frank Gardner said the action came as a surprise to many in Whitehall.
He said: "They would have thought that this would be dealt with internally at the Ministry of Defence and the Cabinet."
The employee, whose name cannot be named, will be charged under paragraph 8.1 of the Act, the clause dealing with the secure storage of information.
The Royal Public Prosecutor's Office recommended that the officer be prosecuted by the Metropolitan Police for the highly sensitive nature of his work in the Joint Intelligence Committee.
The documents he released included classified assessments of al-Qaeda and the capabilities of Iraqi security forces.
He was informed of the decision on Monday morning and was taken from his home to a secret location.
Housing associations face B&B costs
British housing associations could face costs of more than 80 million pounds after the rescue of Bradford and Bingley banks.
The government provided £14 billion to protect the deposits of Bradford & Bingley's 2.6 million customers.
The interest on this loan is paid by all companies that receive money from investors, including the 59 construction companies.
The director general of the Association of Housing Associations (BSA), Adrian Coles, said it was "intolerable" that the companies and their members had to pay.
The $14 billion loan will eventually be repaid when Bradford & Bingley's loans are repaid.
But the interest accumulated in the meantime is credited each year to the 700 financial firms that accept deposits.
The Financial Services Compensation Programme confirmed to the BBC that the 59 housing associations were included in this figure.
It is bitter that those institutions that have behaved prudently ... It is now being called upon to bear some of the costs of those institutions that have been far less prudent.
Adrian Coles, BSA
It said that each company would have to pay in proportion to the deposits it would hold, and that the companies together would have to pay about 18% of the costs.
The Treasury estimates that interest on the loan will amount to £450 million in 2009.
This means that the companies have to raise 81 million pounds for the interest of the first year.
Adrian Coles, the director-general of the Association of Housing Associations, told the BBC that he believed this was unfair.
It is bitter that those institutions that behaved prudently during the housing boom are now being called upon to bear some of the costs from those institutions that were far less prudent.
According to the BSA, no society has failed since the records were established in 1945.
"We will be monitoring all aspects of this matter over the next few weeks to see what alternatives there are to protect housing associations and their members from potentially significant costs."
The interest due in 2009 covers the seven months from the end of September this year to the end of March.
In 2010, interest will be due for a full year and that could be almost twice as much.
Since construction companies are bilateral organizations without shareholders, their members will have to pay for the costs either through higher fees or lower interest on savings accounts.
Turkey broadens diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey aspired to join the European Union, the European powers were interested in penetrating deep into Turkey's hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps within Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the guidebooks tell you.
The building sits at the end of the platforms with a tower at each corner of the front and thus looks like some provincial German town hall.
The rock is dirty.
The whole building is falling apart
But once inside the arched ticket office, there is no doubt about the grandeur of the project, of which this was the westernmost entrance.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Company.
Germany, which was a latecomer in the imperialist game, intended to implement its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by rail connection to Damascus, Baghdad, and further beyond what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperialist plans faltered during World War I.
Its railroad tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation from its surrounding region, created by the insurmountable borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
British forces moved out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was also bad news for Hyderpasha Station.
In 1917, an ammunition train blew up, destroying the ornate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly disintegrated, largely ignored by history.
Today, however, this railway line serves, at least symbolically, as a gateway to Anatolia and everything east of it, highlighting the expansion of Turkey's diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has introduced a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from neighboring regions created by the borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
Now there is a policy of rapprochement.
Remarkably, the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian splinter groups Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to assess the fundamentals of this new foreign policy, I boarded the night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on tracks that produced the lockstep of the old world in the well-known documentary "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is seen as a new city for the new secular state plan to turn its back on the Ottoman past.
But the AKP, known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity.
This has sparked some mistrust in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, a custom-built, ultra-modern stone and steel structure, in a developing suburb surrounded by half-finished shopping malls and pubs where middle managers in suits, both men and women, met to close the first deals of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a Blackberry.
"The goal of the party's foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbors.
The Cold War was an exception," he tells me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Nowadays it has to look east and west at the same time.
There would not be either one or the other.
She would have to do both.
"But surely Turkey could be forced to decide at some point," I asked.
"Turkey," he said, "did not want to have to face this decision."
He then emphasized a point that almost everyone I spoke to almost routinely recited: Turkey's relations, not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, Europe as a whole can, figuratively speaking, travel east towards Asia and the Middle East on the same railway tracks.
Back at Hydarpasha's train station, after another largely sleepless night, I thought of these two German gentlemen, Mr. Ritter and Mr. Conu, who had watched the construction of this structure 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that much of Europe's ambitions in the Middle East could now be in Turkey's hands.
And as I waited at the pier for the ferry that would take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe" in those days.
At the time, at least, there didn't seem to be much doubt about which continent should have a claim to this fascinating country.
Milk becomes five pence per litre more expensive
