New investigation into the US Attorney Affair
The U.S. attorney general has hired a special investigator to look into the dismissal of the nine prosecutors in the U.S. in 2006.
The occasion was a report by the Inspector General of the Ministry of Justice, in which the actions of the administrative staff were criticized.
The report criticized White House officials, lawmakers, and former Attorney General Alberto Gonzales.
The investigation was driven by fears that the lawyers had been dismissed for political reasons.
Special investigator Nora Dannehy is now to clarify whether the officers interrogated during the investigation lied to investigators in order to obstruct justice.
Serious allegations, including criminal activity, have not been fully investigated or clarified, Inspector General Glenn Fine said in his report.
Appointing a special investigator with the authority to compel witnesses to testify was one of his main recommendations.
The conflict began when the Justice Department removed nine U.S. attorneys from office in December 2006.
At the time, the ministry argued that prosecutors would be fired due to poor job performance.
However, it was later found that the dismissed prosecutors had been judged no worse than many of their colleagues, leading many observers to regard the dismissals as politically motivated.
Some of these prosecutors were involved in the prosecution of senior Republican members of Congress, while others had refused to investigate allegations of Democratic voter fraud.
U.S. attorneys are tasked with investigating and prosecuting court cases on behalf of the government.
They can be dismissed at any time, but may not be removed for political reasons.
