Meat Loaf's epic song to be honored
Rock star Meat Loaf is to be honored during the music award ceremony "Q Award" for his epic anthem "Bat Out Of Hell".
The singer, who will accept his special gold award during the ceremony in London next week, said he was honoured to be recognised.
The song, which lasts nine minutes and fifty seconds, was the title track to Meat Loaf's 1977 hit album.
"Coldplay" leads the nominations for this year's awards after being shortlisted in four categories.
The editor-in-chief of "Q Magazine" Paul Rees said that there are some songs that go beyond such matters as time and genre and "Bat Out Of Hell" is certainly one of them.
The song, written by Jim Steinman, required a powerful voice provided by Meat Loaf.
It begins with an instrumental part that lasts almost two minutes.
The song was released as a single in the UK in 1979 and reached number 15 in the charts.
However, Meat Loaf's "Bat Out Of Hell" has spent about nine years in the charts and sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
