Obscure street in town, often forgotten and possibly soon for sale
New York City has thousands of major thoroughfares, avenues, side streets, and other bypasses, some famous and others just convenient.
Still, even for seasoned taxi drivers and longtime locals, it's hard to tell where Extra Place is, simply because most have never heard of it.
This tiny street is located in the East Village and runs north from First Street between Bowery and Second Avenue, without reaching Second Street.
It is 30 feet wide and 120 feet long and looks more like a dusty alley than an actively used thoroughfare.
There are also no road signs.
It is practically impossible to find them on a standard road map.
This street still has its admirers.
For example, Avalon Bay, a construction company that recently constructed luxurious buildings on First Street.
It wants to repave Extra Place to create a clean passage to the shops and boutiques that are expected in the new buildings.
Other admirers include the long-standing neighborhood, which says she's fascinated by the short alley, simply because it's one of the remnants of the block's past.
However, the city administration department, which is responsible for the protection and construction of the residential buildings and is responsible for the road, has no interest in preserving them.
During a meeting of the local council's Land Use Committee this month, city council officials and Avalon Bay drafted a proposal for the contractor to purchase the road.
Still, the committee prefers the road to remain in the hands of the city and has asked for a new plan to be presented next month, according to Susan Stetzer, the county manager on City Council 3.
"Very little space has remained in the city's possession and we want Extra Place to continue to be owned by the city," she said.
"There could be offers on how to repair and operate the road, which could be done by Avalon, but we also want public access to be guaranteed."
Avalon Bay announced a few months ago that it would repave the small street and set up seats that are intended, among other things, for a café to which the company wants to rent space.
The idea that Avalon Bay could buy the road was first made public during this month's meeting.
Michele de Milly, a spokeswoman for Avalon Bay, said that while the company wanted to use the road, it didn't necessarily want to own it.
"The main concern of Avalon Bay is to renovate this dilapidated alley and make it a public meeting place," she said, adding that the city itself had proposed the sale.
Seth Donlin, spokesman for the Department of Facility Protection, said it was indeed the city's desire to sell the street, stressing that the department's job was to develop rather than manage the properties.
Compared to its colorful neighborhood The Bowery, Extra Place has retained some of its historic touch.
Some believe that the road got its name in 1802, when a large farm owned by Philip Minthorne was divided between his numerous children and a narrow strip of land was not claimed by anyone.
The back door of the music club CBGB, the punk rock monument that closed in 2006, opened to Extra Place and the street is probably best known as the backdrop for the photo on the cover of Ramones' album "Rocket to Russia".
The patch was great, said Danny Fields, the Ramones' manager, who took the photo in November 1976.
The street was full of scrap, rags and parts of barrels, posters, leaves and ropes.
Some residents, including the bloggers who write about the gentrification of the East Village, have rejected the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that this public property, as modest as it is, should remain public.
Others have hailed Extra Place as a rarity – a virtually unchanged splinter of the city that should be left alone.
Jeremiah Moss, who runs the blog called "Jeremiah's Vanishing New York" (subtitled "The Book of Lamentations: A Bitter Nostalgic Look at the Dying City"), has published part of the city's history conversation about Extra Place, which appeared in "The New Yorker" magazine in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote at the time: "Extra Place is a small narrow cul-de-sac that remains dark even during the day and is characterized by rusted metal doors of the warehouses, locked windows and week-old newspapers flying past rain gutters".
With few exceptions, the street looked exactly like this recently on an evening.
A rat ran through the back of the street, not far from the door that used to lead to the CBGB, where a more expensive clothing store is now located.
Graffiti could be seen on the walls and an empty beer bottle lay on the floor not far from a fresh bundle of discarded newspapers.
Some passers-by said they rarely thought about Extra Place, but suggested the street could be brushed up a bit.
Fields, added that in his opinion, some people underestimate the allure of the road in its current state.
The best years of my life, he said, were in the places that were dark, damp and disgusting.
Bilingual Education Debate: Education in English-speaking Environments
In this issue of Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss candidates' positions on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior research associate in California Studies and senior director of the Department of Education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not As Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs School Selection."
Appealing to Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama's proposals on education are a case in point.
Obama's campaign mentions that "African-American and Hispanic students are less likely to successfully complete school than white students" – which is true.
To close this achievement gap, Obama's education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transition period in education for those who are just learning English.
Still, Obama's question is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching languages other than English, runs counter to his interest in narrowing the gap in school performance.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently arrived in the country, are learning English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent fourth-grade students passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of the children from the fourth grade were rated as good in the English exam.
This astonishing success was achieved by methods other than those favored by Obama.
The Sixth Street school emphasizes review and practice, constant monitoring of knowledge, and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
Furthermore, the school practices the approach according to which the education takes place in an English-speaking environment. That's exactly the point Obama should keep in mind, according to Principal Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasizes the almost exclusive use of the English language in subject teaching.
Mrs. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico. 12 months later, you would enter the classroom and no longer be able to recognize it.
"It works," she noted, "it works for us."
Would Obama use a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for other schools with large numbers of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The school's performance would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational policy positions within his own party (national education associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education make predictions about Obama's answer uncertain.
While agreeing with the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about "English only" legislation.
Instead, he said, "You should make sure your child knows Spanish."
If Obama really wants to close the performance gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work, rather than despising and trivializing them.
