Team record set by series in the second quarter
Central defender Shaun Ellis thought he had seen it all after wearing a Jets jersey more than anyone over the past eight and a half years.
Then he saw the second quarter on Sunday, in which the Jets turned an inconclusive game into a triumph.
"I've never seen anything like it," Ellis said.
After a sloppy game between the Jets and the Arizona Cardinals, which corresponded to the bad weather, the second quarter began.
However, when quarterback Brett Favre's pass arrived at Lavernues Coles for a 12-yard touchdown, it marked the perfect start to an afternoon in which their evolving collaboration took a giant step forward.
Favre found Coles in that quarter for two more touchdowns, one slipping as a full-back and the other time 10 seconds before the end of halftime.
"I didn't try very hard," Coles says of the passes that went to Coles.
"He's a super player.
Our vote was right, no matter what people think."
While Favre and Coles played catch, the defense took quarterback Kurt Warner apart.
Full-back Darrelle Revis intercepted an unfortunate shot and turned it into a 32-yard touchdown.
Libero Erik Smith got another pass and intercepted it.
Linebacker David Bowens then caused a loss of Warner.
The last ball loss, forced by Bowens, was probably the craziest one.
The Cardinals had captured the ball with 10 seconds left in the game when the Jets recaptured the ball and Jay Feely converted a 20-yard shot for a 34-0 lead.
That was the most points the Jets had ever scored in a quarter.
