Rested Gebrselassie beats his world record
Haile Gebrselassie from Ethiopia has once again shown why some consider him the best long-distance runner of all time after breaking his own record in the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to complete the distance of 42.2 kilometers in less than 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With the victory on the flat course in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie has improved his previous result of 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he had achieved last year in Berlin.
Gebrselassie, 35, has set his 26th world record in his versatile career, in which he has achieved at least one world title or set a world record on every distance from one kilometer to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic marathon for fears, perhaps exaggerated in retrospect, that air pollution could exacerbate his asthma problems.
Instead, he has registered for the competition in Berlin.
In almost ideal conditions - in the sun and 9 degrees at the start and 13 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie won at an average speed of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since track runners such as Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat from Kenya switched to long distances, the record time for marathons in the last 10 years has fallen by more than 2 minutes since Ronaldo da Costa of Brazil won 2:06:05 in Berlin in 1998.
After his victory on Sunday, Gebrselassie told the press that he had cramps in his calf two weeks ago and was therefore unable to train for a week.
Obviously, he came back refreshed after a break and not rusty.
"I'm so happy," he told reporters.
"Everything went perfectly.
I resumed training a week ago and still had some concerns today, but in the end everything was great."
He has been criticized – particularly in Kenya, Ethiopia's rival from East Africa – for over-orchestrating his races, avoiding many of the world's top marathon stars in general, relying too much on race leaders as if it were a track race, and putting world records above competition.
But this criticism hardly harms Gebrselassie's greatness as a long-distance runner.
Accompanied by four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie had reached the center of the course in 1:02:04.
Two elite runners from Kenya, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi continued to challenge Gebrselassie after the pacemakers slowed down.
Just over three miles before the finish, Gebrselassie made his last run to part ways with Kwambai, who finished second in 2:05:36, improving his personal best by almost 5 minutes.
Kamathi was third in 2:07:48.
For women, Irina Mikitenko, originally from Kazakhstan and now German, has completed a remarkable year by showing the seventh fastest result of all time with 2:19:19.
The world record of 2:15:25 is held by Paul Radcliff from Great Britain.
Last spring, 36-year-old Mikitenko surprisingly won the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the games in Beijing due to problems described as a back injury. However, she recovered to win in Berlin and improve her personal best by five minutes in her third marathon.
She cleverly planned her run by letting a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners run away, but overtaking them after 30 kilometres.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia was second in 2:21:31, while Helena Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
The pride and hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Tucked away among the excesses of Orlando's theme parks, a few miles from the glittering, noisy and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet town where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first all-black town in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is not as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Nowadays it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee joined the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, the city she describes – and which made her a tourist destination by including her in the Florida travel guide produced by the Federal Writers' Project during the Depression – is in many ways a place of a very special kind.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open conversation about racial relations, many here continue to tire of being watched by outsiders.
"We're very concerned about how our story is told," said Hortense Jones, 59, a city resident by birth and a parishioner of the city's oldest church.
It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 inhabitants where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is on the one hand a stronghold of literature and on the other hand an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
Not surprisingly, residents here are both proud and on guard.
And the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in heartfelt books written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida travel guide transformed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that runs through the often forgotten center of Florida, into the scenes of black history and human drama.
Cheeky as Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private matters.
"Off the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-and-white painted modern school, with its manicured gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always takes care of, though he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned widow Dash's new husband, writing that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever suits lesson rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls Hurston immortalized by quoting the men who sang songs about their beauty, which were full of sexual innuendo.
She added, "Some people didn't like this."
Hurtson is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came roaring into town, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and dressed in pants, in a city that even today imagines something about her venerable style of dress.
According to Mr. Franklin, most residents were fascinated, while many despised them.
"People were always happy to see Zora," Mr. Franklin said.
But "she never stayed too long," he added as he rocked in his chair, on a rear terrace overlooking Sabelia Lake, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no grand memorial service, no public readings on a grand scale.
"I don't think they understood their contribution to the world or their legacy in the slightest," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
The turning point came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to lay a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's slow two-lane main road.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made while Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 50s, the fight against miscegenation brought hatred into the community.
"During that time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting aside," Mr. Franklin said.
"There was even a woman who was killed once.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand to force integration, calling its decision in the Brown case against the school board "offensive rather than respectful of my race."
Residents now say that while desegregation was positive in some ways, it weakened group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black kids were used to being hugged — I remember — you hugged your teacher in the morning and you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group for the protection of the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because he was a white teacher — I mean, there's a cultural divide," Ms. Nathiri said.
However, civil liberties have helped make room for more Zora Neale Hurstons – black writers, actors and artists who defied prejudice as she did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, "How can anyone deny himself the joy of my company!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker made her way to Hurston's nameless grave and began fighting for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much-praised Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway hit bookshelves, making it once again part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came at a time when Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans for a five-lane highway enlivened the city, accelerated the whole thing at top speed, aroused real civic pride," Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd put it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the self-image of the city.
More and more newcomers came, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been attending church here since 1993, and locals began to appreciate the past anew.
Eatonville was added to the National Historic Register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
These days, Eatonville remains a peculiarity in Florida: just 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a backstreet in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(She's 90% black these days.)
Outsiders in search of Eatonville's history and significance are often still treated with caution.
Most interviews require prior permission and certain things — such as the mural of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man depicting black men working in the fields — may not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a brave, confident teacher with a penchant for dark red, still fear that her shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time as the Hurston Festival grew, an increased degree of homeland pride was born.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville the way Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better, and just as proud, creative and hardworking, silly and mixed as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city council or the police that he says could use some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just drive through here will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Alondra Kenon said the other day after church.
"But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it's a very beautiful city."
Here in New York, financial Latin is fluent.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newsstands and massive TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn't realize they were in the middle of a debacle.
They would never believe that above their heads, in the shoebox-like offices with the glass facades, bankers and hedge fund managers who have the monopoly in New York, have the worst day of horror work every day since the stock market crash of 1929.
The suppliers still push the metal tea carts along sidewalks with loud clatters and carry trays loaded with muffins for the breakfast sessions.
Latinos still shuffle between apartments, like human pack animals loaded with some 50 ironed T-shirts hanging from a yoke-like pole lying on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting for their breakfast bags at food stalls on the sidewalks, and it's still impossible to get a yellow taxi between 4pm and 7pm on a weekday.
It didn't feel like a crisis at all until I decided to open a new savings account on Thursday afternoon due to all the doomsday talk.
Although I had decided to schedule my duty to the quiet late afternoon in my JP Morgan Chase main branch, there were already about 20 people queuing up.
Not at the cash counters to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service counter where regular customers order checkbooks, ask tourists for directions to Macy's and where new customers open accounts.
Most of the people in front of me, I later learned from Starr, my "licensed personal bank clerk," were queuing for the same reason I did.
unlike me, however, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks in places where they commuted from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called thrifts (a bit like a building society), cooperative banks and those local savings banks that only have branches in one state and say they treat their customers like family.
Last year, 15 of these banks quietly went bust.
In the last few days, Washington Mutual, a $327 billion bank, went into receivership, and when New Yorkers drove home for the weekend last Friday, Wachovia, another bank that owns $440 billion worth of savings, was looking for a bailout buyer.
Fearing another collapse, the office and store workers who lined up before me took their cash to a safe haven bank, a bank responsible for most of Wall Street's bailouts.
Ordinary New Yorkers have acquired fluent financial Latin in recent weeks.
A woman who was on the phone in my Chinese supermarket referred with so much familiarity to Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank and its emaciated-looking CEO Dick Fuld, as if she were gossiping about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the 50-year-old uniformed concierge of my apartment block, has strayed from our usual entertainment topics about Brad and Angelina and my grocery delivery.
"I now have all my savings in money market funds," she told me after my visit to the bank.
"I've changed, I'm not taking any more risks."
In memory of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's musical director since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (obituary on September 11) was responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic and choir.
As part of his music program for the city, he founded his great youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
It was intended for young people up to 21 years of age, but when the choir sang for the last time in 1979, some of us were already in our late 20s - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological form changer) stood for the willingness and ability of the choir to tackle any piece of music that was presented to it, whether it was a madrigal or from the Messiah, whether a capella or with a full orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often astonishing, always exciting and lasted solely thanks to the inspiration of that man and his enthusiasm for music, which never diminished for years.
How many times did death encourage us to "let the music speak for itself".
He used to say: "The composer knows what he wants."
It's all in music.
So sing it!"
His way of conducting was absolutely clear and precise, never bossy but never exuberant.
However high the musical level, he always demanded an even higher one.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the last two decades, from 1962 to 1982, when he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic.
In the last 40 years or so I have written reviews for over a hundred of his concerts and I can honestly say that I have never been disappointed by a single one - often I have been inspired by them.
Tod Handley was that rare combination of greatness and personal modesty.
He loathed conductors who, in his words, simply "peddled one or two well-known show horses in the world."
So many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
In your obituary for William Woodruff (25 September) you write that "he resumed teaching economic history at Oxford in 1946 and received a Houblon-Norman Research Fellowship in 1950... while studying for a BSc, an MA and a PhD degree at the same time.
This is a conclusion from an author's note in Woodruff's book "Beyond Nab End", but it is not true.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham and during this time he wrote a doctoral thesis on the British rubber industry under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers, which was later published in 1958 as "The British Rubber Industry".
He was in the United States from 1950-1951 on a Houblon Norman Fellowship, and spent the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953 he left Nottingham for good and went to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff wanted to cover up this part of his career.
Muslim graves desecrated during rightward slide in Austria
Heinz-Christian Strache, a left-wing member of the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party, and Filip Dewinter, a member of the Belgian right-wing Pertei Vlaams Belang, take part in a demonstration in Antwerp on Thursday, January 17, 2008, to represent the organization "Cities Against Islamization."
They carry signs in the style of road signs on which a mosque is depicted, crossed out with a red line.
Police are accusing right-wing extremists of desecrating graves at a Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend that far-right parties are making significant gains in the country's general election.
In the night from Friday to this morning, more than 90 graves at the cemetery in Traun near Linz were severely damaged in an action organized according to police.
The perpetrators spray-painted Jewish symbols such as the Star of David on some of the graves, but detectives believe this is an attempt to disguise the motive of the extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether the incident is in any way related to the elections.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the grave desecration, which took place as the religious month of Muslim Ramadan drew to a close.
At the same time, Austria is facing a round of conscience after the country slid to the right in yesterday's parliamentary election.
The FPÖ and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, the two far-right parties that won almost 30% of the vote, campaigned for a strict anti-immigrant law and some of their slogans were criticized by opponents as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, leader of the FPÖ, which won 18% of the vote, campaigned for a ban on headscarves and burqas and even expressed his aversion to foods generally associated with Islam.
At his last rally in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties want to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of a continuous Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses conducted immediately after the election, which say that the far right is the politically strongest bloc in the country, suggest that this new development is based on young voters worried about their future in the European Union.
Foreign travel ban for Gary Glitter
Gary Glitter, the glam rock star convicted of child sexual abuse, has been banned by court from traveling to France and Spain.
Judges imposed a six-month ban on Glitter after he informed the authorities controlling him that he wanted to travel to Spain via France.
Police in Kent were granted a travel ban last Thursday after presenting judges with evidence of Glitter's criminal record of child sexual abuse.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at Ashford District Court in Kent, but was represented by the law firm Corker Binning.
A spokesperson for the Court reported: "On Thursday 25 September, Kent Police applied to Ashford Magistrate Court for permission to prevent Mr Paul Glad from travelling abroad to France and Spain until 25 March.
Paul Gadd was not present in person."
As required by the Sex Offender Register, Glitter, 64, had informed authorities that he wanted to travel abroad.
He must inform the authorities if he wants to travel abroad for more than three days.
He must also notify the police 7 days before his planned departure.
Failure to notify the authorities could result in a prison sentence of 5 years.
Police in Kent said they would not discuss individual cases or Glitter's possible whereabouts in the country.
A spokeswoman for Kent's police force said: "Kent police will do whatever is necessary to protect children in this country and abroad."
"In our view, it is easier to control someone who is in the UK because we have a comprehensive system in place to effectively prevent any potential risks."
"It is the top priority of Kent police to protect Kent residents and we are working closely together to monitor the behaviour of registered sex offenders in the country to minimise any risk that may exist to the population.
Glitter returned to the UK last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for abusing 2 girls, aged 10 and 11.
When he was released, Glitter flew to Bangkok, where he was scheduled to take a flight to London.
But he said he didn't feel well and refused to fly to London.
The Thai authorities did not let him through passport control and he flew to Hong Kong after some back and forth.
Chinese authorities also denied him entry and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and border officials insisted that he return to Britain.
Finally, he arrived at Terminal 3 at Heathrow on 22 August and stayed there while his lawyer David Corker went to the Uxbridge District Court in West London, as Scotland Yard had successfully asked for permission to register as a sex offender.
Glitter had previously been imprisoned in the UK for 4 months in 1999 for possession of child abuse images.
According to the Home Office, Home Secretary Jacqui Smith was reassured and satisfied that Glitter was prevented from travelling to France and Spain.
'I receive the master backstage to capture his character,' says Günter Brauer, photographer.
No heels, no frills, no costumes for the performance.
The nature of the great flamenco dancers who renounce concentration and devote themselves to interpretation in order to get a relaxed look as a woman or as a man.
On the one hand artist
On the other hand, personality
I look into private life, into those moments that are foreign to the audience, I know when I can find gestures typical of the personality, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of the hands that are worried because they will not enter the stage.
In his project 'Flamenco-people', the German photographer Günter Bauer depicts varied theatricality of some productions on stage with singers, dancers and guitarists. From this side he was still little known to the artists.
With this proposal, the photographer creates a particular iconography of flamenco representation on different levels.
The exhibition, which is part of the program of the Flamenco Photography Month, "reflects the international importance of flamenco, which is increasing day by day," explains the artist, making it clear that 'flamenco people' "can be any human being, but if you look at the photos, the viewer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
Ordinary people in the portraits are artists who are able to convey passion, sadness, joy on stage and thus move the audience.
In order to capture the personality of these artists, you don't have to take photos on stage.
Her personality and character is in their hearts.
What interested me was to create a personal atmosphere that would allow me to capture the characters of the greatest flamenco masters with the camera'.
Bauer, inspired by the festival 'Cante de las Minas', embarked on a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a digital camera.
Thanks to the image sorting function of the camera and the existing material, images were created that are reminiscent of classic photography.
The application of various stylistic means destroys the classical basis of the image, giving the image modernity and the idea of how the peasant understands flamenco: 'music with traditional roots that changes and surprises every day'.
These are not only the dance, the singing or the instrumental playing itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, who seduces the audience with his art.
The search for the essential, for a certain something, which becomes visible in the form of hearing, of being, is and was the fixed goal of this work, which will be presented in the gallery of El Fotómata in the near future.
Well-known personalities in flamenco among them Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo and others are among the shortlist of the nearly seventy artists photographed.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco and will soon be published as a book, with all the portraits from the exhibition.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to take up this idea again two years ago and realize it as 'portraits of the veterans of sports' ('SportARTproject').
Although the concepts of the project 'Flamenco-people' are different, the photographer admits that 'I really like photographing people, getting to know them and putting myself in their state of life, be it for a short moment or a longer period of time.
I think that in the field of photography, portraiture is the most difficult genre.
You meet or bump into people, personalities you sometimes don't know at all, or they leave you alone for a few minutes to take a photo.
Apart from these circumstances, as a photographer I always try to realize my ideas.'
The collection of portraits of flamenco of today, entitled 'Flamenco-people', is exhibited in the gallery of El Fotómata, located in the street called la calle de la Mata and parallel to the street la Alameda de Hércules. The exhibition can be visited until 16 October.
Vargas Llosa admits that the Roma he is writing is 'foolhardy'.
He does not yet know where the plot of the novel takes place and what it is, but Mario Vargas Llosa persistently tries to advance the project he is currently working on, a novel with the protagonist Roger Casemant, a nationalist from Ireland who lived in the Congo for twenty years and moved to the Amazons.
Yesterday, during his presence at the Hay Festival Segovia, the favourite Nobel laureate admitted that the project he is engaged in is 'foolhardiness' and 'everything indicates that he would not have to write the novel'.
'If I had been level-headed, I wouldn't have done it, but I will and hope to finish the novel at some point,' so he concluded his participation in the festival, where the ideas, thoughts and words were exchanged. Within the four days he saw hundreds of writers, historians, journalists and thousands of people who were in Segovia.
The author of 'La ciudad y los perros' was one of the most outstanding personalities at the third festival and made predictions.
Vargas Llosa, who won Premium at the Hay Festival and voted for most of the attendees, is compared to the old edition of 'Our mutual friend' and can be seen at the Juan Bravo Theatre.
He was introduced by Félix Romeo and realized that he had an audience in front of him who realized that the Peruvian, who has a wonderful memory and great sense of humor, was not given enough time to go through everything again: how his vocation to literature came about, born out of 'extraordinary adventurousness', from 'the joy of reading' and from 'wanting to experience more',  than before'; how he writes and 'maintains discipline' to supplement 'the lack of inspiration', his intensive work with documentation, numerous corrections and revisions that he makes; how Faulkner, Víctor Hugo and Alejandro Dumas influenced his vocation and what 'memory images' form the basis for his stories.
The Hispanic-American novelist acknowledged that there is "no way" to measure and how to know if books change lives, "but I refuse to believe that literature is pure entertainment, a fleeting experience," Vargas Llosa insisted, who claims it 'creates effects' and 'makes people even more apart'.  that is why I asked writers to 'abandon themselves to lightness' and 'take responsibility' for his vocation.
At the festival in Pozoblanco, the weather did not play along: bullfighting festivals were partly cancelled.
