In Álava, two people wanted to avoid control of their car, which was loaded with two thousand kilos of hashish.
Tomorrow: five minutes to ten.
Traffic controls in Ertzaintza, in the urban area of Armiñon (Álava).
Two police officers asked the drivers of the car to stop, whereupon they fled.
It looked like they wouldn't have to stop with the cargo of more than two thousand kilos of hashish.
The police pursued them and arrested one of the drivers, the man, who is 28 years old, known as A.A.J., according to the Ministry of the Interior of the Basque State.
The arrested person was charged with drug trafficking and falsification of official documents.
The incident occurred when the officers of the traffic police of the Álava region had already completed the traffic control on the N-1 and drove past the urban area of Armiñon.
They decided to stop a car to carry out the route control. The driver did not follow the instructions, suddenly increased the speed and tried to evade control.
The police started the pursuit until the car stopped after a few kilometers at the hard shoulder. At that moment, the drivers got out of the car to flee over a country road into a wooded area.
The police of the city of Ertzaintza finally caught up with one of the two. In the car, an Iveco Daily, the drug traffickers transported 2,178 kilos of hashish, which was confiscated by the police.
The front part of the car was loaded with bundles of hashish, which were later sent to other police stations for detailed laboratory analysis and weighing of the bundles.
In addition, the officers found that the license plate was 'double', so that it did not match the number plate indicated in the vehicle documents, which is why an additional arrest for forgery of official documents took place.
The police of the city of Ertzaintza are continuing the investigation in order to arrest the second suspect who, as already mentioned, managed to escape, but also to establish the origin of the drugs seized.
The arrested 28-year-old A. A. J. was taken to a police station for questioning. He will be brought before the magistrate in the next few hours.
Actress Heather Locklear was arrested for driving under the action of an unknown drug.
Actress Heather Locklear, known for playing Amanda from the series "Melrose Place," was arrested this weekend in Santa Barbara, California, for driving under the action of an unknown drug.
A witness had observed how she tried in a rather strange way out of her parking space in Montecito, reported spokesman for the traffic police of California the magazine 'People'.
The witness told in detail that Locklear 'pressed the accelerator pedal after 4:30pm and made a lot of noise by trying to move her car backwards or forwards out of the parking space, and as she reversed, she grabbed her sunglasses a few times'.
A little later, the witness, who had probably not recognized the actress at first, saw that Locklear stopped on a nearby road and got out of the car.
The witness was the person who notified the emergency services because she was 'afraid for Locklear's life'.
When the police patrol arrived, they found the actress sitting in her car, which was standing across the road and blocking traffic.
"She seemed disoriented," so the police took her to a special drug and alcohol center to take a test.
According to a police spokesman, the actress was cooperative, excessive alcohol consumption was excluded from the first moment. "According to the initial observations of the officials, we believe that Locklear was under the influence of an unknown drug," the spokesman said.
Locklear was arrested on suspicion of driving under the influence of an undetermined substance that could not be determined and taken to a local detention center around 7 p.m.
Two months ago, Locklaer was discharged from the Arizona clinic after treatment, where she was being treated for anxiety and depression.
Llamazares insists that the Andalusian United Left will be responsible for the Silva case.
Gaspar Llamazares, the main coordinator of the VL and deputy of the United Left, has assured today that the regional association for education will be the one that will make the decision in the case of the former Councillor for Youth and Sport of the City Hall of Seville, Francisco Manuel Silva, who resigned last week after being accused of doing business with family members.
"In such cases, I am a great federalist, and the Andalusian organization will be the one that will have to take responsibility for this," Llamazares pointed out, pointing out what approach the party must have towards who, until now, sits as a councillor in the municipal council of Seville.
Nevertheless, the chairman of the VL defended the need for 'transparency' in the possible investigations of the rule violations that Silva may have started: 'The VL always insisted that such cases be given maximum transparency'.
With regard to this issue, he stressed that education has "a strict ethical code for all public offices".
'Sangre de mayo': Book of heroes by Garci
Inspired by 'Episodios Nacionales' by Benito Pérez Galdós, José Luis Carci depicts in 'Sangre de mayo' the revised version of the famous uprising of the Spaniards against the French. This is an admirable film in the filmography, with about 15 million euros investment for the shooting.
In this way, the cineaste has tried to 'portray a lot of personalities and social analysis', which he has always admired in the works of the famous novelist, Carci explained today at the presentation of the film with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría at the beginning of a long list of actors.
'Sangre de mayo', with a film length of more than two and a half hours, will be presented in cinemas this Friday and later shown on Telemadrid as a four-hour miniseries.
José Luis Garci, a big fan of Galdós' literature, assures us that thanks to this filming, his 'childhood dream' came true. He owes this to Esperanza Aguirre, who three years ago commissioned him from the Community of Madrid to shoot a commemorative film for the second centenary celebration on 2 November in Madrid. Especially because the story is based on 'Episodios Nacionales', he accepted the commission.
The total contribution of 15 million provided by the Community of Madrid for filming offers Garci, he added, the 'unique opportunity' to portray the image of 'confused Spain that chose the wrong leader for the struggle because the people had been put behind by the struggle for independence and under the rule of Ferdinand VII'.
However, the cineaste regrets that one could not count on the financing as in 'Alatriste' or 'Los fantasmas de Goya' (twice as high as in 'Sangre de mayo'), so some scenes from the script with Horacio Valcárcel, with whom Garci worked almost his entire career, could not be shot.
For this reason, Garci, who was also film director in 'Volver a empezar', participated through his usual way of working: he stood on stage with the actors with whom you have to rehearse before you start shooting and for those who had not done a casting, he seemed 'humiliating' and respectful, 'part of the profession of film director is to  To help in the theatre and in the cinema to know what is happening in the cinema industry in which you work.'
Many of the actors he encounters in 'Sangre de mayo' have to repeat in front of his camera, as in the case of Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larrañaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
Garci, Oscar nominee in four nominations (one of which he won), is of the opinion and assured that none of the three candidates representing Spain before the Academy of Hollywood this year represent a young generation of Spanish filmography. Neither 'Sangre de mayo', nor 'Siete mesas de billar francés' and finally not the selected film 'Los girasoles ciegos'.
Garci does not expect any awards for this film.
'In the beginning you think you're working for the offspring, later you realize it's just for thriving, and now you're satisfied when you've produced another film,' explains Garci after more than 30 years of professional activity.
Isabel Bayón recalls the memory of the dancer from Seville Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville worships a dancer who is also from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalan (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and her mother Andalusian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in the Triana district and when she was three years old her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and expert in oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first fighters for the emancipation of women, like Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, vegetarian and campaigned for the abolition of the corset that restricted free female movement.
The life of this woman, who left her mark on the dance and aesthetics revolution in Europe in the period between the wars, fascinated Isabel Bayón.
'I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this role to me, which seemed impossible to me.'
'We try not to talk about her life, but to preserve her spirit,' said the flamenco dancer.
Their dance basics helped me a lot in flamenco.
For example, 'The Dance of the Butterfly' seemed to me like guajira, or 'the dance of the snake' like tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I was told that my dancing was also in this aesthetic realm," she claims.
The production anticipates two extraordinary collaborations: with Miguel Poveda, who will sing again for Isabel at one of her performances, as he did in 'La puerta abierta'; and with flamenco master Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work together with one of her ex-students.
'Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work and I am very honored.'
