'Car bee' that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, this time Nissan was inspired by nature, more precisely, by the bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight is based on the swarm behavior of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C and represents the first step in accident prevention technologies.
The engineers from the Technical Development Center of the Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in cooperation with the Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, head of technology PR and R&D brand management, the BR23C represents an extension of the four-layer Nissan safety shield.
This robot is designed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid the collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds its own oval-shaped flight space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important thing are the compound eyes of the bee, which can see over an angle of 300 degrees in all directions, which allows it to fly undisturbed in its personal airspace without interruption.
In order to simulate the all-round perspective, the technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF).
It detects obstacles in front of the BR23C at a distance of up to two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor, which is immediately translated into signal for avoiding the collision.
"The moment an obstacle is detected, the little robot will mimic the bee flight and immediately change direction by turning its wheels 90º or even greater angles to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference to other arbitrary systems is that this evasive maneuver takes place absolutely instinctively.
If it were not, the robot might not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the lead engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate upwards or downwards, but also not overheaded; it can only move on two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in the infinite directions and in infinite ways as bees do.
For this reason, in addition to acceleration and deceleration functions, Nissan has used the rotation function so that the small robot avoids the collisions.
'This device only needs a few seconds to process the information and act on that information.
It does not require either the information or the intuitive logic of the maneuvers made, so it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This sounds surprising, but it's not about the GBs and not even the MBs of storage space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for immediate collision prevention, a technology that Nissan predicts to introduce in production cars over the next decade.
The robot works with lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than a variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite to guide you to the destination while driving, avoiding the obstacles on the way.
Motorists who may relapse due to alcohol levels will have to install the 'Alcolock'.
The authority orders that the driver, who had three official penalties for alcohol levels, install this system in his car, which prohibits him from starting the car while drunk. If he is drunk, then the car does not start.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the Attorney General's report. According to them, it is a pilot project that will last one year.
The purpose is the resocialization of the driver, which is why he gets a course for the re-education of traffic behavior.
In addition to the Prosecutor General's Office, experience has shown that the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for Automobile Safety will also participate.
According to statistics, between 30-75% of drivers who were reported more than once for driving under the influence of alcohol got back behind the wheel.
The 'alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents autostart when the driver has taken a breathalyzer test; or if an alcohol concentration is detected that is higher than allowed.
It costs more than EUR 1 000 and is borne by the person imposing the sanction.
In this context, a study conducted in the USA in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of rule violations in the first year after its introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved annually.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate their implementation, a lawful reform can be realized in the usual way, and yet a reform of the Basic Law is demanded, which is necessary for the prosecution process.
The device is not yet available in any store on the Spanish markets, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
Tomorrow, of all days, the Chamber of Deputies will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses. This has already been done in France.
