Conversation - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
Above all, it has regained public trust, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service were contaminated with HIV and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public discontent, in February 1994 the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry, led by Judge Horace Krever, with the aim of shedding light on the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and developing guidelines to prevent another disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still reluctant to give his report, several provinces set up a committee whose goal was to develop a new system for administering blood in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Company, to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood storage system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood and through the work in this area during the following years, we have regained the trust of the public," she says, before proudly emphasizing that in early 2008, almost 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its founding on September 28, 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on a prudent basis.
At that time, we witnessed the emergence of numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't have the slightest idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which exclusion measures are applied if you do not know this and if a disease progresses slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself through degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So, in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago it was proven beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
So this event showed us that the principle of caution that we applied makes sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NSTs), which make it possible to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, rather than that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NSTs made it possible to shorten the incubation period that takes place between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
This has significantly reduced the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it and that this could not be detected.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving blood infected with HIV.
"In other words, you would have to distribute 12 million blood units before someone would be infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood units each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV was transmitted via a blood reservoir occurs.
I believe that nowadays you can feel comfortable getting or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore health," says the director of Hema-Quebec.
"Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
Only last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects via the blood.
We need to monitor continuously," Dr. Décary continues, before stressing that Hema-Quebec must provide adequate supplies in addition to secure supplies.
"Demand is increasing because the population is aging.
Because treatments to fight cancer are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which on average includes only 3% of Quebec's eligible for blood donation. '
Any healthy person who is 18 years or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is prevalent are excluded from donating blood for one year.
"With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But the members of this donor network must be renewed as they grow older and can no longer donate blood.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but most importantly, to keep them and get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that it's rare to find the time to spend an hour donating blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin used almost exclusively for severe burn injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being temporarily stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec's only public cord blood bank.
The umbilical cord, which used to be considered biomedical waste, contains blood rich in stem cells, which can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth cord blood sample, and we plan to take more than a thousand annually.
"We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year," explains Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Many mothers are convinced that they do not have access to it," because Hema-Quebec lacks the resources to offer this complex and costly program in all hospitals in Quebec.
