Charest focuses on the north
The Prime Minister does not rule out launching elections before the end of the year.
As soon as the general assembly of the liberal party was over, Jean Charest went yesterday to Jean-Talon in Quebec, where the new health minister Yves Bolduc (left) is trying to be elected in today's by-election.
'Shifting the course of our last great border in the north': this is the long-term goal that Jean Charest presented yesterday by visual means at the General Assembly of the Liberal Party of Quebec in Levis, following the guidelines entirely.
During his lecture, a kind of picture mill was projected behind him.
On three huge screens were spectacular images of hydroelectric power plants, mines, Quebec viewed in 'Google Maps', maps, etc.
Large resources, as during the parliamentary term.
Speaking to the press, the Prime Minister refused to rule out the possibility of holding elections this autumn, even though he said that his schedule was very full.
The 'Plan North' is the fourth element of a 'vision' the Prime Minister claims to have for Quebec, namely that of a 'new economic area' involving an agreement with France on labour, an agreement between Canada and Europe, and agreements with Ontario.
Although it has been mentioned frequently in the Prime Minister's speeches recently, the opening of the north - the northern area on the 49th parallel - had never been the subject of a presentation.
However, the prime minister confined himself to explaining why the North was 'a jewel with enormous potential', but did not give a date, investment amounts or precise priorities for the projects to come.
At most, a few glimpses of what could be worked on more: mainly in hydropower, in forests, but especially in the mining sector, favoured by the growth of emerging economies and the renewal of public infrastructure.
According to Mr Charest's list, the North has 'nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium and even diamonds'.
This 'territory twice the size of France' is close to us, is in Quebec.
It is not only close to us, it is in us,' he stressed, as if to clearly show that he is seeking to realize a national entrepreneurial dream.
Quebec has grown a lot through its connection with the North, he pointed out: the road to gold in Abitibi, the technology of Quebec, the Bay of James.
"It's ours, it's our future," he added, after pausing theatrically to look at the giant map behind him.
The north, 70% of Quebec's territory, includes a part of Labrador that Quebec has always demanded, the prime minister told the press.
"This is a traditional attitude that all governments have followed.
There is a borderline where there has been no agreement for a very long time, if the opportunity arises I will take this position again on behalf of the government," he said.
In addition, "with climate change, we need to rethink our vision of the North," he said, talking about the Northwest Passage, which will be navigable year-round due to melting ice.
Against this new geopolitical background, the Prime Minister believes that it is almost a duty to occupy this area.
And the inhabitants of the area, the indigenous people and the Inuit?
The Premier said that the Quebec government would be very careful with them, and that they would benefit from this project, especially the young.
Two former ministers from different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former Pekist MP for Ungava), have already initiated consultations with some thirty communities.
A Committee of Ministers headed by Benoît Pelletier, in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Mineral Resources) occupies an important place, has started work.
The Prime Minister does not rule out a large gathering, 'not necessarily a summit', but an opportunity to 'create a common vision'.
The development of the North will also take place in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
Plan Nord will be 'discussed, regulated and environmentally friendly', he promised.
Jean Charest described this 'vision' as if it were a continuation of that of the liberal prime ministers who had been in office before him.
"Like the Liberals who came before us, we have rethought to turn the challenges into new opportunities for growth and development.
This, by the way, was one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which opened on Friday with a big cocktail party to celebrate the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage taking over the leadership of the party.
One of the adopted decisions provides for the Beauharnois power station to be renamed the Adélard Godbout dam.
"From Godbout, who created Hydro-Quebec, to Lesage, who achieved the silent revolution and nationalization of hydroelectric electricity, to Bourassa, who made James Bay, our party always knew how to determine the future," Jean Charest explained.
He referred to another, this time conservative, project to the press, namely the 'Roads to the North' programme of John Diefenbaker, Prime Minister from 1957 to 1963.
With regard to the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydropower dam project, Mr. Charest emphasizes that its commissioning is scheduled for 2012.
'That remains between us, but I intend to be there,' he confided to his party members, which provoked storms of applause during those parties.
Indeed, the Prime Minister, who said in April that there would be no elections in 2008 and certainly in 2009, has not yet ruled out the possibility of holding an election this autumn, which he is legally able to do.
However, he stresses that his schedule is full, mainly because of a Community Council mission to China and a summit between Quebec and New York.
The weekend's General Assembly provided the Liberal party leader with a platform of nationalist plans, above all 'constitutional objectives' that were readily adopted: the PLQ specifically calls for recognition of the 'specificity of Quebec' in the constitution.
It also wants Quebec to appoint members of the Council of Canadian Broadcasting and Telecommunications, and for them to have a veto over decisions made in Quebec.
On the part of the opposition, the guidelines of Plan Nord were received with scepticism.
The leader of the Parti Québécois, Pauline Marois, has revived the Nord-du-Quebec development policy introduced by the Landry government in 2001.
According to her, when the Liberal government came to power in 2003, it refrained from applying it.
If she had done so, 'we would have been much further along today', said Ms Marois alongside her candidate in Jean-Talon (where the election is taking place today), Françoise Mercure.
The ADQ has spoken out in favour of supporting the government's adoption of a Plan North.
"But what we want is that this is not just a big performance," declared party leader Sébastien Proulx on behalf of Mario Dumont, who is returning from vacation today.
Letters - A Dishonored Land
It was Mr Vic Toews, ex-'justice' minister (ironically) in Harper's cabinet, who last summer took the liberty of saying of Louise Arbour that she was a 'disgrace' to Canada.
This woman, who has waged a never-ending battle for justice and deserves all our admiration to cover with shame, says as much about the people around the Prime Minister as she does about Stephen Parker himself.
We are dealing here with a government which, among all the countries concerned, has not brought home its compatriot who was imprisoned in the Guantanamo concentration camp.
A government that does not even take into account that Omar Khadr was still a teenager when the things he is accused of happening happened.
The only government that, despite the fact that Canada is a signatory to the Geneva Convention, breaks its word and lets a child soldier languish in inhumane conditions.
The only one who condescends to a parody of justice in order to assess the guilt of the accused.
Let us remember that UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Association of Canadian Lawyers in particular are calling for Omar Khadr to be brought home so that he can get a fair trial in Canada.
It is precisely this government that closes its eyes to torture: it cares little that a young adult will surely be mentally broken forever after so many years of torment.
We are not yet aware of this, but we are witnessing an insidious curtailment of our rights, our freedom and our 'democracy', this word that Harper constantly carries before him like a flag, and which sounds so meaningless from his mouth.
So the time has come when there is no morality at all: you can arbitrarily abuse, torture and imprison a Canadian citizen, at the discretion of a head of government who is still supported only by the minority (may he belong to the minority after October 14...).
Many voters believe they will find salvation in a party that preaches virtue, law and order. But they do not see that this government has renounced what made up the reputation and dignity of our country.
The shame, Mr Toews, lies in this detachment, and nowhere else.
Free Speech - The Orwellian Speech of Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Deputy General Manager of the Canadian gold mine Barrick Gold.
He confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the world's largest gold mining company sought a six-million libel suit against three authors and a small penniless publishing house with the aim of opening a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, then they are not judging the truth, especially not in the case of libel suits, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to bankrupt anyone who dares to hold one of their opposing opinions.
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and editor of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money to prepare their defenses and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
Moreover, the tactic in these unequal battles is often to ruin the defenders in order to force an amicable settlement that silences the other side and also deters anyone who dares to revisit the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it would have had to present its point of view to public opinion.
In contrast to what is common practice in many of the countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada debates are usually fought through the exchange of ideas rather than by stick-blows.
It would therefore have been enough if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened a real debate, through the newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent audit teams that could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion, brushing aside petitions and letters in support of Noir Canada's authors with a wave of his hand.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can at the same time ask for a 'public' debate and at the same time disregard the opinions of that very public?
Apparently, in the world of the Vice President, this word encompasses only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a rather narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand—or doesn't want to understand—is that the public, who support Noir Canada's writers and editors, do so primarily because they reject the gold mine's brutal stance.
This public is willing to listen to Barrick and judge, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gag complaint (in the course of the 'public debate', Barrick Gold has just made a demand to the authors of Noir Canada, demanding that they stop using this term...).
Aside from Mr. Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic inquiry and truth-making that are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it's impossible in a country like Canada to research and discuss issues that the world's rich corporations don't like, who else can?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could have it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment, to which we belong, has long known how to get a grip on debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for transparent debate.
This is a loss for the academic world, as well as for public debate, and it's time for governments to take action that curtails these types of unwarranted lawsuits.
Bailout for Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans get along
The Bush administration and senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most comprehensive economic bailout plan since the Great Depression of the '30s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to stop the financial crisis that has been rocking Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both chambers of Congress.
The main contents are: better control by MEPs over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public funds invested, new orders to curb the number of houses seized due to arrears, and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the executives of the supported companies.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative present at the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, after a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will have a market impact," said Bush administration official Henry Paulson.
"Everything was done to protect the real economy and the American people from the Wall Street price crisis," the Democrat said.
"This is the fundamental point: If we don't do that, the trauma, chaos and unrest in Americans' daily lives will be enormous," said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had accelerated over the past two hours, fearing the impact that another failure would have had on investor sentiment.
The deadline that had been agreed was the opening of the market this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who were late in the negotiations, were more likely to be in favour of the agreement, but without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the need to meet them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on the addition of certain executive orders to the settlement, most notably those that would allow owners to keep their homes and those that affect the salaries of executives of companies bailed out by the state.
"Asking taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain people is nothing to congratulate ourselves on.
But these measures are necessary," he said on American television.
When asked on another network whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied: "I'd like to know the details first, but I hope so.
"The guiding principles I've read [show] that this is one thing we're all going to have to digest, and we're going to be able to move forward with.
The option of doing nothing at all is simply not acceptable," he said.
The $700 billion plan is designed to use taxpayers' money
It comes 14 months after a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of high-risk mortgage lending (subprime) before spreading to other forms of more common bonds (PCAA), and finally to a freezing of financial strength and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican lawmakers who failed last week's first attempt at agreement.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain 'toxic' assets of societies in distress should only be secured by the government and not bought, one believes that the impasse has escaped.
To round out the perspective for everyone in Congress, an executive order has also been added stating that if the government were to make losses on this program within five years, it could then levy new taxes to recover the capital it had invested.
The new plan calls for the payment of an initial sum of 250 billion, to which another 100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion must be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In return for its help, Washington receives shares in the supported companies that pay it dividends in case of profits, and which it can sell again when the storm passes.
The Federal Government will have the possibility to halt the attachment proceedings concerning the apartments tied to the real estate loans affected by this plan, and also to set deadlines for repayment and severance payments to be paid to the executives of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on it today, and the Senate then on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
In fact, more voices were raised yesterday against this project, both from the Republicans and the Democrats.
"Obviously, Washington doesn't understand us," Republican Scott Garett, a member of the chamber's finance committee, told his constituents.
'Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists of making taxpayers pay'.
Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman, head of a group in Congress called "the skeptics," presents things differently but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred distinguished economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to tell us: We ask Congress not to be pressured and to carefully consider which path to take," he said yesterday.
At the same time, we in Europe were once again proving that this is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would refrain from buying up its competitor, which has been in deep trouble since losing 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) in the crisis due to the risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
To compensate, we are given the right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what savers and households value now that uncertain times are looming. '
During this period, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government was in the process of nationalising another bank hit by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all current loans at the bank Bradford and Bringley, including over 41 billion ($75.5 billion) from real estate loans.
Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the British bank's branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank after Northern Rock that the British government has had to nationalise since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (19252008) - Death of a dedicated icon
His beauty with the azure blue eyes was his trump card for a long time, no one would say his weakness.
Had the American actor with the charming smile freed himself from the narcissistic mirror?
Yes and no.
His sensitivity, sensitivity and obvious talent have also kept him away from a position of power that gives birth to the truly horrible monsters.
But what a great endurance runner!
Paul Newman, who died on Friday at the age of 83 from lung cancer on his ranch in Connecticut, remains one of the last icons of American cinema during the golden years.
He was less monumental than Brando, whom he resembled and for whom he was for a long time a kind of rival on the screen, more careful in his acting, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breaking of dramaturgical conventions.
Mixed blood often makes wonderful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925 to a German Jew and a mother of Hungarian descent.
His European roots were to become one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, utmost quality feature.
Because it reflected an entire country that was in love with the self-made man, with the fighter who was wounded in battle in the Pacific War, who studied acting at Yale in the early 50s and then visited the Actor's Studio in New York before he had success at the theater, on television and soon in the cinema.
This same man who fought for civil rights was also the driver who finished second in the 1979 24 Hours of Mans, and also a sex symbol, although he had been in a model relationship with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With him also disappear the unknown facets of this mysterious, reserved, committed and oversensitive to the glamour of show business star, whose mystery will never be completely solved.
A decent man, in the purest sense of the word.
The death of Paul Newman sent cinema lovers into a frenzy this weekend, while all his great roles were played out on the dark screen of memories.
More than half a century of American cinema in constant change passes by with him.
The charming cowboy from "Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid" (1969) comes back to mind, and the young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on the Hot Tin Roof, which was filmed by Tennessee Williams in 1958.
It evokes a much more recent memory (1990), that of his sensitive Mr. Bridge, who in his old age is disturbed by a wedding that did not fulfill all its promises.
There have been so many other Paul Newmans throughout history.
This criminal, stormy, violent and unforgettable boxer Rocky Graziano from Somebody Up There Likes Me by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, resumed after his death and which made Newman famous in 1956.
This likeable crook in the outstanding The Sting, who won the Oscar for Best Picture in 1973.
As a bitter and vengeful billiard player in the wonderful The Hustler by Robert Rossen (1961),
That face through the ages, that was him.
Still him.
His curriculum vitae unites epochs.
Young people know him best from the cult film Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, the less orthodox coach of an ice hockey team.
His fans found him in The Coen brothers' The Hudsucker Proxy in 1994.
With a final role in 2003 as Godfather of the Irish Mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes, the circle closed.
Unlike several cinema legends who retired early enough from the film world, Newman was supposed to stay in the saddle for a long time, betraying Hollywood, his fortune, his pomp and his concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier saw him, not without humour, as a living challenge to 'underplaying' when he judged his overly expressive performances.
The profession was not always easy for the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles flew for a long time.
However, he rarely played sunny boys as outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, villains or desperate, with whose perfect portrayal he reflected his slide and rebellion.
As a director, Newman revealed unknown sides of his true sensitive sensibility.
His Rachel, Rachel from 1968 (based on the novel by the Canadian Margaret Laurence) with his wife Joanne Woodward in the lead role, drew a subtle portrait of a woman full of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated his 1984 film Harry and Son, a work full of sensitivity and sadness.
In the flood of tributes pouring over Newman yesterday, his close friend and former comrade-in-arms Robert Redford (they had starred together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) declared with great emotion: "His presence has improved my life and this country."
Generosity and joie de vivre were essential characteristics of the late actor.
Apart from his legendary career, a great advocate of civil rights, environmental protection and independent cinema, an opponent of Hollywood's drift, is now also leaving.
We have probably often seen him with his foot in bowls full of vinaigrette, in sauces, pastries or other foods, and thought this was quite tasteless, although we found it funny at first.
Nevertheless, the profits from his sales flowed into his foundation for children in need.
Instead of resting on his myth, Newman engaged until the shot.
He left his five daughters a letter with these sentences: 'Always and until the very end, your father was incredibly grateful for his good star.
It was an honour to be here. '
And for us, it was an honor to follow the life of such an intelligent and generous American actor.
An exemplary citizen, in the narrowest and broadest sense.
What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag &amp; Co.?
On 8 October, the trial of János Zuschlag and his accomplices begins.
The defendants are accused in particular of participation in organized crime, as well as grossly negligent damage and business fraud, and other criminal acts - including falsification of documents.
According to the public prosecutor's office, the funds obtained from the tenders were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often documented with fake invoices.
State funds and subsidies from the local government - a total of HUF 65 million - are said to have flowed partly into the coffers of the organization Fiatal Baloldal, partly into the private coffers of individuals.
As the investigating authorities announced, fictitious invoices were presented when receiving the tender funds, and the clubs are said not to have fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were forged.
The invoice blocks were bought at the Józsefváros market, the round seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision on which companies to issue the invoices to was decided on the round trip north of Lake Balaton, on which István Lados was sent by Jáno's surcharge.
In the course of this "exploratory tour", Lados was to locate guesthouses and restaurants.
He demanded invoices for the consumptions in order to be able to issue invoices for the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the local government of Budapest based on these templates.
The majority of these invoices are said to have been manipulated by István Lados and his accomplice, András Őri, who, according to our information, was responsible for drafting the corresponding reports.
One of the destinations of Lados' "exploration" was a beer bar.
As can be seen from two invoices issued by Zuschlag and Co in 2003, the catering business is said to have entertained the ninety-member group of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
Now, however, the boss of the company states that such a large group would not have fit into the restaurant all at once.
Another invoice, issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, also had serious errors in form and content.
In a guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj, which has only three rooms and can accommodate no more than ten people at the same time, 130 guests are said to have stayed.
There were apparently no limits to the imagination of the invoice forgers when it came to Pigal Kft., a catering business in whose accounting documents of the customers Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá do not even appear, according to the prosecution.
As managing director Győző Farkas told the hvg.hu, it was immediately clear to him that these were forged documents when documents were presented to him by the prosecutor's office during an interrogation.
"Our company name and tax number were incorrectly affixed to the stamp".
And further: Apart from formal errors, the fact that the establishment is said to have accommodated one hundred people was also wrong, since they have a total of eleven rooms, which cannot possibly accommodate so many people.
Catering was also listed on the invoice, although the restaurant had not been in operation for a long time.
The diligent invoice forgers also failed to verify that the Budapest travel agency they targeted only offers trips abroad, and so they indicated trips to Hungary on the cash invoice, which also contradicted the company's accounting practice.
As it became known in the course of the investigation, they also stated VAT on the invoices, although travel agency services relating to a country outside the EU are exempt from VAT.
The amount of VAT on a total of four invoices issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation was incorrect, as the company charges only 15% VAT instead of 25, and only machine invoices are issued by the employees, but the forged documents were handwritten.
Another mistake made by the "accountants" was that in one case they had declared "transport of goods" as the service provided, although this is not offered by the firm specializing in investment advice, the prosecutor's office said.
Thanks to further formal errors - wrong invoice format, wrong stamp - the invoices issued to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, as well as to XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont could be exposed as forgeries.
The same applies to Ravenna Bt. and the Kunfehértó sports camp, whose managers claimed never to have issued the invoices.
Another "mistake" was made by the counterfeiters at HIB Kft. from Nyíregyháza: this company was in dissolution at the time (2001) when the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group is said to have eaten there - the trustee in bankruptcy therefore stated that he had not issued the invoices himself.
Deliberately forged
The other group of accountants are people who were well aware that they would have to submit fictitious invoices.
At the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, the Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation issued invoices for the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Foundation in the amount of approximately HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the managing director of Collab Kft. was persuaded by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue the fictitious invoices.
Biogate Kft., which is also currently in liquidation, is also said to have cooperated with Zuschlag and Co.: In 2003, the GmbH is said to have supplied the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation and the associations Atlasz Egyesület and Vörösfenyő Egyesület with forged invoices with a total value of HUF 5 million relating to services not provided.
However, there were also no payment transactions, since the invoices were cancelled immediately after they were issued, which the persons concerned forgot to note in their documents.
The third group of accountants includes persons who are directly associated with the accused.
One of them is Iván Kubatov, the postman of the Ukrainian CEO of Delta Trió Kft., a fuel and vehicle trading company based in Budapest but cannot be found there.
In the period from October to December 2005, that company is alleged to have issued several invoices for the sale of computer components with a total value of HUF of approximately 18 million.
According to the investigating authority, Cash Investment Kft. from Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005, acted as the purchaser of these invoices.
The managing director of this company was a Romanian, to whom the company documents were also to be served by Iván Kubatov, between 2002 and 2005.
According to our information, Kubatov confessed during the investigation to having issued invoices in the name of the LLC to the associations Atlasz and Hoppá, as well as to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and to have collected their equivalent value himself.
The companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. are said to have been founded by Romanian bricklayers at Iván Kubatov's express request.
In reality, however, none of these companies were active, which, according to the defendant, was due to a lack of orders.
Nevertheless, he was able to benefit from the companies: at the request of his accomplice, the lawyer Zsolt Szente, who was responsible for preparing the company formation documents, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to the associations associated with the award, such as Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
In total, Kubatov is said to have issued 15 invoices with a total value of HUF 14.2 million to the organizations on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade.
The public prosecutor's office assumes that Kubatov could have collected 10% of the invoice amount as well as the VAT.
Kubatov is even said to have misused the company Szi-Beri Bt. for the issuance of fictitious invoices - in this case, the invoices were attached to the applications of Biztos Pont.
In January 2006, Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted their applications to the non-profit organization of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány ("TMA").
Both received 500,000 forints each, but used these amounts for other purposes.
In order to cover this up, they presented the TMA with five fictitious invoices from Works Team Kft.
Incidentally, these invoices were seized during the search of Árpád Kemecsei's office in the Ministry of Education.
During the trials, some defendants are now expected to confess to the procedure of falsifying invoices, as they have already been filed before the public prosecutor's office.
A sensation could be if the main defendant János Zuschlag decides to make a full confession.
His previous statements were less detailed, and although he had already promised several times to report comprehensively on everything, his confession is still pending.
The question therefore remains whether this is in his interest, whether the Socialists have concluded a pact with him to make good the bulk of the damage of HUF 50 million, and whether Zuschlag is prepared to accept responsibility in return.
However, it is quite possible that Zuschlag is now playing the "offended" after his requests for mitigation of detention and house arrest fell on deaf ears.
While other criminals, who have caused far greater damage with economic crimes and have not compensated them, are at large, or at least under house arrest, Zuschlag is denied this possibility.
The psychology of outbidding – or why we're willing to pay more
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue what is offered for sale.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic basis of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in "Science" magazine, people do not want to admit defeat in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was supposed to play the lottery, while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, participants could win money, but increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, in which outbidding the opponent plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to substantiate their thesis, the economists in the research group have also carried out studies on the tracking of money.
In this case, three groups should bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was told the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they emerged victorious from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in case of a lost game.
The only difference between the two groups was that the emphasis was on winning while the other was on losing.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the "against losing" group were willing to bet higher than those in the control or "win" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have justified the behaviors observed at auctions so far only with the joy of winning, or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to neurological imaging, so we now have a third explanation ready," said Andrew Schotter, Professor of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is due to the fact that the patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, however, the pathogens and the diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as semen, vaginal secretions or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B, but there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and eyes, the stool becomes light, urine dark, and recovery can take up to two-three weeks.
Around 1 million people worldwide die every year from hepatitis B-triggered, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people is undergoing drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this condition is more common: those who underwent blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C sufferers worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
If detected in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby averting the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by patient advocacy groups worldwide.
The aim of the campaign is to raise awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, its development and the importance of early detection.
Benelux governments nationalise parts of Fortis Bank
With a partial nationalization, the Benelux countries want to help the Belgian-Dutch Fortis Bank, which has been in turmoil due to the US financial crisis: The three states are providing a total of EUR 11.2 billion to the banking and insurance institution, which also has branches in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held high-level discussions over the weekend, together with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commissioner of the European Commission's competition authority.
In the eurozone, Fortis is the first victim of the international financial crisis, which has been going on for a year, so decisions now being taken in connection with the bank could set a precedent.
In line with the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states are buying about 49 percent of the bank's respective shares.
The bank is expected to sell some of its holdings, most notably the insurance activities bought by Dutch ABN Amro last year.
Fortis shares began a steep slide last week, and serious crisis scenarios were already emerging in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank, with its 85,000 employees, is far too big for a bankruptcy.
The institution's securities fell 12% to a 14-year low on Friday.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Given the current share prices, the market value of the group amounts to EUR 14 billion, which is unrealistic according to management.
According to management, the $700 billion US bailout and the resulting uncertainty in the markets are to blame for the decline in Fortis shares.
On Monday, however, prices rose slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank's new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for a private buyer, but no interested party with a factual offer was found.
The Belgian government, however, was trying to calm down - no investor should tremble for his money, it was said.
So far, no panic has broken out among customers, the bank's branches have not been stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent branches, but it also owns leasing companies.
Do believers have less pain?
As the latest research results show, religious faith acts like a kind of "painkiller" that is said to have already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment: It was examined to what extent belief in God influences people's perception of pain, reported the British newspaper "Telegraph".
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and 12 atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
Using a brain scan technology, it could even be proven that the Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participate.
In the experiment, a sparkling device was tied to the left hand of the subjects, which delivered the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with an Ermine".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a kind of religious trance among the faithful while choosing da Vinci's image because it was little different from the other painting and was perceived as soothing.
The subjects each spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while looking at either the religious painting or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt "safe" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were "cared for", and they felt "peace and quiet".
While looking at the religious painting, they reported over 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be created with other, strong-looking images in the atheists, one would just have to find the corresponding photo.
"We would have to find an image that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," says the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practicing the faith should change our personality, and it does in many cases," Wright said.
After these excellent results, the only question that remains is what effect a Madonna painting by Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On the occasion of her tenth birthday, Google can justifiably claim: she can be found in people's pockets as well as above their heads in the sky: She knows where people have spent their holidays, which specialists they go to, and what moves them.
And that's not all, according to Eric Schmidt, one of Google's CEOs.
In the direction of skeptics, who are plagued by Orwellian horror visions, he says: These would overlook the essence of Web 2.0.
In a recent interview with the Financial Times, Schmidt said Google's main goal is to collect even more personal data about users, moving closer to the company's original goal of "organizing all the information in the world."
Schmidt explained that after ten years of world-changing work, Google is still only at the beginning of collecting information.
Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said that he wished Google was able to answer questions such as "What should I do tomorrow?" or "Which job really suits me?", but software programs are not yet able to do so because they do not know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that in the course of their Internet research, the search terms would be registered, as well as the IP addresses from which the search was made and the pages visited.
For example, the "Personalized Search", introduced two years ago, allows the visitor to save his own search history and access it later, so that the hits can be generated much more precisely later, and the same logic is also the basis for the so-called "recommendations", with which the system recommends tailor-made products and services based on previous preferences.
However, users wonder what happens in the event of data misuse - "If you look up what I do" - some are concerned about Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is the potential power represented by the company that is frightening, rather than guilt or fear of punishment, the pursuit of freedom, or rebellion against power that is rejected by many Internet users.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored, but also passed on to third parties if necessary, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A prime example of this was the recent crackdown on pedophilia in Brazil, where Google provided the Brazilian government with information collected by the community site called Orkut, which also allowed the pedophilia to be identified.
However, users concerned about personal rights could still breathe a sigh of relief in May, when Google, together with the civil rights organization EFF, successfully took the FBI to court: according to this, Google cannot be forced to hand over information to the FBI on secret request with any point of the Constitution.
(However, the Federal Government has successfully obtained the publication of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms with reference to the Youth Protection Act passed years ago, but the list of individual users, or their web and search term list, was withheld retroactively for two months.)
Google's image thus remains controversial: Those who are reluctant to give over their personal data because they fear the loss of their privacy and intimacy by using Google services castigate the company with the indignation due to the conservative companies.
Meanwhile, the American "geek culture", which is present in many countries and unites enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, sees in them the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs", in contrast to Microsoft, which is the market leader thanks to Windows, even if both are fighting for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that, unlike Microsoft, Google does not require its users to provide identification codes and provides its services free of charge, so an open, constantly updated source code and program package seems far more attractive, youthful and cool than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, the geeks see through the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet - a relationship that has come to the fore, especially in recent years, thanks to the term "Web 2.0".
"Web 2.0" is about nothing more than collaboration, i.e. the users deliberately leave traces and use the available communication channels, and even if the dimensions are individually different, the main thing remains the same, namely to show themselves publicly.
An average teen can manage their profile on several community portals at the same time - from Facebook to Xanga, can connect them through other services, such as Twitter, or music services such as last.fm, and can finally integrate all this into a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. In addition, they can run blogs that automatically display the latest photo galleries listed on Flickr or Picasa.
And a number of other exemplary cases prove: When looking at the party photos of the previous night, the girlfriend soon finds out with whom her unfaithful boyfriend has had fun, or the employee is dismissed because he is all too honest in his blog his anger about the company management - one thing is certain: The term "privacy" has now been completely reinterpreted.
Whoever leads an online life is what he reveals about himself - this is how you could formulate the basic idea behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who tries to keep something secret, or even to circumvent the Google monopoly, is welcome to do so - as with Scroogle, a tool that accesses Google's search engine, but intentionally leaves no trace.
Quite a few people deliberately do not register on community sites so that they cannot be found, but Google's online applications, such as word processing and graphical tools and RSS feeds, can also be handled with alternative versions that are not tied to huge server parks and therefore do not generate the best possible profile from the user.
Public opinion, meanwhile, is waiting spellbound for Google to show its true face.
With its current value of USD 156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca-Cola (USD 110 billion), the advertising space of AdWords/AdSense threatens the revenues of advertising agencies, and the ever faster introduction of services is a headache not only for Microsoft but also for other software developers.
Critical observers, however, also find the disturbing opposite poles: For example, the company management completely rejected a protest by employees after the fees of the company's own kindergarten were doubled, and the management also said that the repeated catering of the employees was too expensive. However, all this seems downright mild compared to the fact that Google even bowed to the Chinese government in 2006 and agreed to an agreement according to which all dissident hits, or those that violate good taste, would be filtered out.
The internal regulation of the group is that no new service is advertised in advance, but only when it is already available. Nevertheless, the events of the coming months and years could turn things upside down: While some believe that Google's book and magazine scanning or archiving project is now taking on proportions that the company will soon have to deal with the Supreme Court, others are more concerned about the "Health" system, which enables the creation of a complete health profile based on findings, doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database is already providing the next generation of sci-fi authors with the material - such as "Scroogled", the famous novel by Cory Doctorow, describes in the best Orwellian manner a future in which a person becomes frighteningly approachable thanks to Google-related data.
