Intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method for developing new technologies for accident prevention if not imitating the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, that of bees.
An amazing project was unveiled at CEATEC in Japan, where Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees to create new accident-avoiding systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system controlled by car robots, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area," which is very similar to our own "protective shield," said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-guided distance meter.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a field of view of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of a second, and the car robot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tires around the appropriate angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If it weren't so, the car robot would not be able to react fast enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield – a layer within which accidents are currently still considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, unlike the bees, the evasion cannot be done up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the manoeuvrability of the tires.
While the bees have an infinite number of possibilities to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use the rotational movement, acceleration and deceleration of the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer lifespan than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond to them accordingly.
It doesn't have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical response based on previous maneuvers, so it only takes up a handful of KB of memory on an ongoing basis.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte memories.
This is the first step in the development of instant collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in series production within the next decade.
Another application of the technology could be GPS satellite navigation by deliberately steering the driver around obstacles and thus guiding him to his destination.
A name for the sinful child
Now the written version of the $700 billion bailout bill is available, which will be applied in several stages and aims to buy the bad loans of the banks.
In the first round, half of the money is to be spent.
In a meeting that ended on Saturday after midnight local time East Coast, the congressmen have struggled after several days of debates to reach an agreement on the $ 700 billion rescue package, Reuters reported.
"We have made significant progress," said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic President of the US House of Representatives, and said that the agreement only had to be put on paper.
The compromise reached on the bailout was supported by both presidential candidates - Barack Obama and John McCain.
Commenting on the outcome, Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said the program will be effective and efficient, but more needs to be done. According to Pelosi, this is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the tide of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets, i.e. Washington time Sunday evening 8 o'clock (Central European time Monday 2 o'clock in the morning), but has not triggered a soaring flight on the stock markets.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will vote first on the 2008 economic stabilization bill, then it will be the turn of the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi on Saturday night, and the White House also welcomed the news of the agreement.
"We are pleased with the progress made during the night and appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our markets and protect our economy," said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
The program, however, differs from the Bush administration's original recommendation that the $700 billion should be spent at once on buying bad securities burdened with loans.
In a first tranche, a maximum of half of the 700 billion amount is to be spent, with 250 billion available immediately after Congress is expected to vote on the case on Monday. This sum is to be spent on the purchase of credit-burdened, bad securities, and the president is to decide on the other USD 100 billion.
The program is reviewed by a separate commission, which includes the President of the Federal Reserve.
The other half of the $700 billion depends on another congressional decision.
Under the law, the Treasury can also use a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy bad loans, mortgages, mortgaged securities, or other "toxic" loans.
As responsible persons of the Ministry reported, the purchase can take place both in an auction, as well as directly.
The law allows the affected companies to participate in an insurance program in which the Ministry of Finance guarantees the worrying funds, and the companies pay fees corresponding to the expected damages.
Henry Paulsen said: The law defines the necessary funds in such a way that up to $700 billion can be made available as emergency aid to the American financial system, whether for the large-scale purchase of bad funds, their insurance, or the avoidance of systemic risk triggered by the collapse of a major financial institution.
"We are taking the necessary steps to get the law ready to be introduced as soon as it is signed," Paulson said.
However, the heads of the troubled banks, which are now dependent on state aid, can expect their settlements, which are casually called the "Golden Handshake" in overseas slang, to be cut by the government.
A cut in salaries will only occur in certain cases, and these cuts will depend on how the Ministry of Finance helps out in each case.
The cut essentially means that if the ministry buys at auction, the "golden handshake" will be taxed unless the retired bank boss is deported to retirement.
In the event of a direct purchase of the bad loans, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that manager salaries are not excessive.
It is also part of the picture that the existing Golden Handshake contracts will not be changed - the restrictions only apply to new agreements, so that the more people participate in the program.
This is the first case in American history that cuts in manager salaries are regulated by law, commented Democrat Barney Frank, Chairman of the Finance Committee, the measure.
The state gains participation rights in the participating banks, so that the risk for taxpayers decreases, as they can also participate as soon as the economy and thus also the rescued bank is better again.
The bill stipulates that the president must submit a proposal to Congress over the next five years on how taxpayers should get back their lost money from the financial sector.
However, there have been skeptics on both sides who have expressed doubts about the plan.
This is not what American citizens expect from us, the plan does not protect taxpayers' money, according to California Republican Darrell Issa.
His colleague from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, said: The measures were driven by the same people who are responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
According to the Central Statistical Office, domestic sales prices rose by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007.
Export prices were 1.1 percent higher than in July 2008 and fell by 3.9 percent compared to the previous year's prices.
Due to price changes in the domestic and export sectors, production prices were 0.7% higher than in the previous month and 3.2% higher than in 2007.
Domestic sales prices rose only slightly compared to the previous month, i.e. by 0.1 percent.
Manufacturing selling prices have also risen only slightly -- 0.1 percent -- since July.
The largest price increase in August 2008 was for leather goods (2.8 percent) - primarily for bags and belts - here the increase was 4.6 percent, for shoes prices rose by 2.5 percent.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials drove up prices for chemicals and production significantly (1.6 percent).
A price decline was recorded for crude oil processing (1.4 percent), electrical and technical equipment (0.9 percent), and slightly for wood processing (0.1 percent).
Prices in paper production, as well as in publishing and printing, remained unchanged.
In other branches of the manufacturing industry, a price increase of between 0.2 and 0.9 percent was measured.
In the important domestic sales markets of industry, such as electricity, gas, steam and water supply, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly as a result of the price increase for gas introduced on 1 July.
Looking at the domestic sales markets of the processing industry year-on-year, prices in crude oil processing rose the most (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking sector, a 13.2 percent increase was observed, while the increase in the production of food, beverages, and tobacco was 11 percent.
A price decline was observed in the textile industry (2.5 percent) and electrical and technical equipment (0.3 percent).
The extent of inflation in the other manufacturing industries was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry climbed by 10.2 percent last year.
Prices for electricity, gas, steam and water rose by 18.7 percent compared to the previous year.
On the domestic sales market, the highest price increase was recorded in August in the fixed goods sector (0.7 percent).
In the manufacturing sectors for consumer goods, prices rose by 0.3 percent, while in the energy and processing sectors they remained the same compared to the previous month.
The largest price increase in August 2008 compared to the same period in 2007 was observed in the energy and re-use sector (16.8 percent).
A price increase of 6.8 percent was recorded in the consumer goods manufacturing sectors, while a price reduction of 1.4 percent was recorded for fixed goods.
Industrial export prices, measured in forints, rose 1.1 percent month-on-month in August, but fell 3.9 percent year-on-year.
The domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro, 7.1 percent against the dollar, and compared to the August 2007 exchange rate, it became 7.5 percent stronger against the euro and the dollar by as much as 15.9 percent.
