Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
The European Summit on Equal Opportunities, which this year is being hosted by France, the country holding the Presidency of the Council of the EU, began today in Paris.
In her speech to the plenary, Lívia Járóka, Fidesz MEP of the European People's Party, drew particular attention to educational segregation, as it is one of the most serious violations of the rights suffered by Roma children and is also the biggest obstacle to their need for recognition.
The high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, on behalf of the French Presidency, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among the participants were representatives of governments, the European social partners, as well as the most important European legal protection and citizens' organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of Fidesz MEPs, Járóka has drawn attention to the fact that, in addition to discrimination in the search for a job, the Roma are being pushed out of the labour market primarily because of their low level of education.
"The vast majority of Roma youth have no secondary education, and thanks to poor primary education, only a small proportion of them can obtain a tertiary education."
Járóka also emphasized that education is a fundamental human right that plays a key role in the assertion of other human rights.
Investing in the early education of Roma children could strengthen the economies of EU member states.
MEPs believe that it is important that the widest possible circle - i.e. Roma and non-Roma - becomes aware of these connections.
The earlier a Roma pupil starts school, the greater his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; and through income tax and turnover tax they contribute to national expenditure.
"As EU citizens, the Roma must be guaranteed the right to quality education - the poor and segregated education must be stopped," said Lívia Járóka.
As the honourable Member said, a common, goal-oriented and action-oriented approach by the European Union is needed to speed up the process of desegregation in the education sector. To this end, correct compliance with the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives is essential.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment and give Roma children the democratic opportunities to contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens," Járóka said.
Since the congress in Berlin last year, the summit has been held annually with the aim of creating a unique forum for advancing the goals of equal opportunities and non-discrimination at European and national level, in the sense of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities".
Fox in the chicken coop
Because of a person's drug use, life and health insurance companies in America often refuse to contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of medication data to the consent of the person concerned in any case.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we will entrust the chickens to the fox," the Washington Post quotes Richard Dick, developer of the prescription data tracking program.
Insurance companies determine the fees and the payout amounts in the event of damage depending on the customer's state of health, and if the risk is overestimated, the insurance is not taken out at all.
Previously, the client was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in the knowledge of the examination results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper method: Based on the customer's identification number, he obtains the data of the last one and a half years from the pharmacies, i.e. which preparations have been purchased, and the program calculates from which disease the customer suffers and what his state of health is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it could be concluded that his blood lipid level is untreatably high, which would automatically place him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so insurance companies only have to do the paperwork, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the disadvantages is that many medications can be taken for different purposes, such as migraines and hot flashes, but also depression.
The latter is a high-risk factor from the insurers' point of view, while the aforementioned ones are not.
For the consultation and processing of the data, separate companies have been formed, which, before obtaining the data, ask the patient for his consent.
In the meantime, they have to do so by law, although omissions have not yet been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory tests and combine them with data on drug consumption. In this way, they provide an even more accurate picture of the patient's state of health.
More and more companies have access to the data, and at the same time it is becoming more difficult to control its use.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect only extends to service providers in the health sector and insurance companies.
The bill has already been submitted to Congress, according to which the agencies could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard realizes that this is not enough, so he wants to develop his program further so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the person concerned.
Another question is, of course, that the person concerned can hardly prohibit access to his data, otherwise the insurance companies do not conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are somehow left to the mercy of the fox.
CSU: Temporary grace
At the end of October, the fate of the fallen duo Huber-Beckstein will be decided
Despite the election debacle, no heads are rolling for the time being, at the top of the Bavarian CSU, the personnel debates have been postponed.
Party leader Erwin Huber and Prime Minister Beckstein remain in office, the only question is how long this grace lasts.
The fate of the tandem after the catastrophic 17 percent loss of votes will be decided on the last weekend of October at the extraordinary party congress.
However, the much-criticized duo has already indicated that they do not want to stick to their chairs.
In doing so, they want to appease the angry faction and the party base, which demanded personal consequences one day after the "Bavarian tsunami" in view of the loss of the absolute majority.
Five years ago - admittedly, under the leadership of Edmund Stoiber, who was at the height of his career - the Christian Social Union reached 60.7 percent. Now, however, one year after the coup against Stoiber, they were only able to secure 43.4 percent of the vote.
For 46 years, the CSU was the "sole ruler" in Bavaria, which generates 18 percent of Germany's GDP.
Although the conservatives remain the dominant force in the southern state, which is also important for the Hungarian economy, they will have to govern in a coalition in the future.
As a first sign of the party's internal restructuring, Huber's potential successor, Vice President and Federal Minister of Agriculture Horst Seehofer, will also be involved in the exploratory team that is conducting exploratory talks with the liberal FDP and the right-wing "Free Voters" about a possible Munich coalition.
It is an irony of fate that with the list "Free Voters" Gabriele Pauli enters the legislature, whose anti-Stoiber appearance the Huber-Beckstein duo first exploited, and then mercilessly dismissed the determined politician.
The CSU leadership is now concentrating all its forces on stabilizing Beckstein.
In this transition process, Stoiber, who has so far pulled the strings from the background, will play an active role. The former prime minister and CSU chairman called September 28 the "bitterest day of his political career."
On Monday, Huber made a few venomous remarks in the direction of the CDU - in his view, the CSU would have deserved far more support from the sister party.
Other CSU politicians interpreted the defeat as a signal to the CDU and thus also to Angela Merkel.
If the CSU, which also contributed much to its success at the national level in 2005, is not put back on its feet with a joint effort, Merkel will not be able to become chancellor again after the Bundestag elections in September 2009.
Merkel, who has made no secret of her disappointment over the fiasco, believes that the CSU's loss of ground will not have a negative impact on the grand coalition in Berlin.
What is relative, however, is that the wounded CSU will not be easier to govern, and the crisis of the Social Democrats continues.
With 18.6 percent, the SPD achieved its best result in Bavaria since 1946.
Lukashenko opposition: 110-0
In Sunday's elections, no opposition MP made it into the Ukrainian parliament.
Russian observers believe this is due to prosperity and stability in the country led by Alexander Lukashenko, but the OECD suspects illegalities in the counting of votes.
The OECD, which sent 450 observers from 43 countries, did not recognise the elections.
The legislature of the 10-million-inhabitant state has managed for decades without opposition. Nevertheless, before yesterday's elections, the opposing party gathered under the name "United Democratic Forces" (ODS) seriously hoped that Lukashenko, who renewed his presidential mandate for the fourth time in the dirty elections and thanks to a constitutional amendment in 2006, would this time "allow" some opposition MPs in parliament.
For this reason, the ODS has even refrained from the previously planned boycotts.
Ukraine is becoming increasingly economically dependent on Russia thanks to rising prices for natural gas imports. Loans have even been taken out to alleviate price increases, and the country has also agreed to sell Beltransgas, the owner of the gas pipeline running through the country, to the Russians. In the background of the opposition's expectations was the hope that Ukraine wanted to improve its relations with the EU after Lukashenko and other high-ranking politicians were banned from entering the EU because of the political system in the EU, which is considered anti-democratic.
The OECD election evaluation report provided temporary relief, focusing on positive movements rather than shortcomings, such as the exclusion of a third of opposition candidates from the elections.
However, the OECD's rapid report on Monday criticized the campaign - according to which opposition members should not appear in the press - and in particular the fact that the opposition was not allowed to be present at the counting of the votes.
Despite all this, the opposition can see an improvement in the political system: political prisoners have been released, for example, and Minsk is even prepared to engage in minor confrontations with Moscow by continuing to refuse to recognize the independence of the breakaway Georgian provinces of South Ossetia and Abkhazia, even though Russia, with which Ukraine forms a federal state on paper,  the two territories have been considered independent for a month.
"We have taken two steps forward and one backward, but the most important thing is that the dialogue between Belarus and the EU has begun," Alexander Milinkevich told our paper.
According to the opposition candidate in the 2006 presidential elections, a continuation is desirable, although "the powerful have become afraid to allow even one opposition member into parliament".
The opposition is not planning protest measures in the face of the results, but rather trying to make the need for economic reform clear to voters.
"We are struggling with a lot of problems here - the opposition newspapers have to be printed in Russia, the local authorities are putting obstacles in our way in terms of distribution, but nevertheless I see that more and more people are supporting the change, even the older ones," Milinkevich said, alluding to the fact that not even the most supported layer of pensioners agrees with the Lukashenko regime.  whose only merit is the establishment of social security.
"Thanks to the country's debt and the increase in the trade deficit, it is only a matter of time before the 'social security' reminiscent of the silence of a cemetery begins to crumble," Milinkevich said.
In contrast to the opposition politician, Russian observers have described the elections as democratic.
Sergei Lebedev, head of the mission of the Commonwealth of Independent States, told the Ria Novosti news agency: "People believe deeds, not words." The absence of the opposition is therefore proof of the maturity of Belarusian voters.
Global menu from Marseille
European Union and India double trade
Since the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, this was the main topic at the ninth summit, among other global problems.
Today is also the Franco-Indian summit, which will mainly discuss cooperation in the nuclear energy sector.
While recognising that India is an emerging, democratic superpower that should be given more voices and a say in international affairs, member states have so far been unable to agree on whether or not to support New Delhi's permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
This issue was not discussed at yesterday's ninth summit in Marseilles yesterday.
French President and current EU Council President Nicolas Sarkozy, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and chief diplomat Javier Solana received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh. An agreement was reached according to which trade is to be doubled over the next five years, i.e. increased to just over 100 billion euros.
Given that trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this goal is not so ambitious.
With this in mind, the 26 existing civil aviation agreements with India have been legally combined into one agreement, so that air traffic will also be boosted in the future.
India wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the pact.
The aim is to strike a balance in the currently unbalanced relationship between the EU and India: while the Union is India's number one partner, New Delhi is only ninth among EU partners.
The summit was dedicated to global concerns.
Among them was the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, respectively terrorism, which both sides condemned in the strongest possible terms. The convening of a UN conference was also urged.
The Doha Round should also be concluded, with both sides blaming the failure.
The EU stressed that it remains committed to its energy and climate programme, i.e. that pollutant emissions should be reduced by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agreed with this, as well as with the proposal to conclude a kind of global compromise at the upcoming climate summit and to reduce greenhouse gas production by 50 percent by 2050.
The rise in food prices should also be combated, so both support the convening of an international conference on the financial crisis.
The Indian head of government is visiting the French capital today, where he will sign an agreement on the peaceful uses of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
