Napolitano: "Prevention of accidents at work is crucial"
Every day in Italy, 2500 accidents occur at work, three people die and 27 remain disabled for life.
For 2007, the data of the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were around 1200.
These figures show the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) will celebrate the 58th National Day for the Victims of Accidents at Work in all the provinces of Italy, in order to draw the attention of social institutions and the media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of recent days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention in the workplace is," confirms the President of the Republic, Giorgio Napolitano, in his message to Pietro Mercandelli, President of Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro).
The Head of State expresses his "deep appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention in the workplace, to the protection of injured workers, to assisting the families of the victims and to raising public awareness".
"An indignant "Basta" has risen to this; understandable in the case of tragedies which, measured by their magnitude, cause some media hype and public sympathy. But everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events that can even repeat themselves in their own momentum."
Napolitano does not hide the fact that "there is definitely a resource problem: there must be decisive investment in education and information."
Of particular importance are the numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness in school settings on the part of young people who are nourishing themselves in the world of work.
It is our duty to draw attention to this phenomenon and not to divert attention from its social seriousness. A legislative standard must be enacted and improved.
For his part, Gianfranco Fini, President of the Chamber, stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency that offends the consciences of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards decisive rules aimed at putting an end to the problem".
"The data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight improvement, but this does not rule out the possibility that the number of work-related deaths is far too high," stresses Pietro Mercandelli, President of Anmil.
"We don't want this 'positive tendency' to mean less attention. That's what causes the tragedy in the end."
"We believe that there is basically too little being done to counter the phenomenon of accidents. You can fight against it through various actions.
In our opinion, stronger controls and inspections are necessary – said Mercandelli; but also stronger measures to educate the workers who already start at school".
"A further effort is needed, he adds, in terms of communication and raising public awareness.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that is a social emergency is needed".
Mercandelli also referred to "the progressive deterioration of protection for victims of accidents at work" and denounced the "abolition of the social system, against which we have been fighting in recent years".
"The aim is therefore to return to the worker a guarantee of insurance, so that the fate of the victim of an accident at work does not become dependent on voluntary or accidental donations decided from time to time by a legislator".
Mp3 player under charge: risk of hearing damage
Listening to loud music for long periods of time with portable music devices, such as MP3 players, can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which quotes the opinion of the Csrseri (Scientific Committee on Current and Recently Identified Health Risks) of the EU in a report distributed today in Brussels.
"It is clear from the report, according to a note, that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music with portable music devices for more than an hour a week for at least five years risk permanent loss of hearing."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who usually turn portable music players and mobile phones to a high volume are irretrievably damaging their hearing without knowing it," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to the EU, the scientific findings show a clear risk that urges swift action.
What really matters is to sensitize consumers and make this information commons.
In the light of this scientific evidence, we need to review the control systems already in place so that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology."
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music devices among young people.
"The scientists - the EU communication concludes - confirm that they are rightly concerned and that the EU Commission, together with the other EU members and stakeholders, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music and similar devices".
There is already a European standard limiting the level of noise from portable music players to 100 dB. The concern about the damage that could come from too much noise pollution.
You can limit this damage very much by resorting to solutions such as reducing the volume and the length of the noise exposure.
In its report, the EU's Scientific Committee points out that if users of portable music players listen to loud music (louder than 89 decibels) for only five hours a week, the legal limits applicable to the maximum noise level at the workplace have already been exceeded.
Those who cross this line with music risk complete hearing loss within five years.
This would therefore affect 5-10% of users of such devices, which can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
Roma, Alemanno launches the "Commission for the Future of the Capital"
We start today, in March it should be over, in June we will take stock.
This is the procedure laid down by the Capitol for the work of the "Commission for the Future of the Capital Rome". The Commission met this morning at the new headquarters behind the Baths of Caracalla.
In six months' time, President Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will draw up the guidelines for Rome.
