According to the court, such transfers (against which the prosecution had objected) could give him the opportunity to influence his company and obtain accusatory evidence.
The elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already been revealed a few days ago, when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the $700 billion austerity package of the White House: A large part of Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's edition of the New York Times, which reports on how the crisis is rapidly dividing the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and the business community, and the neoconservative that is hostile to "those in Washington" and the financial world, winning voters especially in the South and the center of the states.
This part of the party owes its rise above all to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
However, this example just mentioned is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake is heralding, or even already representing: not only in the United States, but also in the entire West and perhaps beyond, it will be affected.
Both in the States and in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the long-feared events which, under these new conditions, are finally taking shape and coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state combined with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis means the decline of banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the wealth of households living in a single state.
This poses a direct political problem for governments: namely, how to behave towards the families concerned, who also represent an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis thus appears economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have been sidelined and lost its right to speak: the plausible proof of this has been given by the EU, which does not know how to find a common path due to its division into various national and international conflicts.
Therefore, everyone is now counting on the intervention of their own state; Rescue plans, new rules, and above all distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis has become more and more serious, only the USA is in the economic situation to save itself without outside help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two conditions that should not be overestimated – under certain circumstances – on which no other international organization and no market will be able to fall back in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the national-national element is, moreover, perfectly in line with the growing importance which has recently been associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now, when we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked empire, into a realm of ever differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, that we suddenly have to realize how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
While these can certainly all be transported from one place to another in the world, they are nevertheless outerly connected to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory has an advantage over another who lives in an area without crops, waterless or free of oil deposits.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a brief insertion.
Whoever says territory, who says government, who says politics, also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to generate two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, i.e. the need for someone who knows how to do things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation against the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a sense, even more worrying aspect: a loss of trust, an intolerance, an image of inexpediency, a sense of remoteness, all directed at an entire class of managers in Western countries.
It seems that the conviction among large parts of the population is paving the way that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content presents itself to the majority as ever more alien and outdated.
The demand for leadership thus feeds underground a ramified but powerful movement of disempowerment of the ruling class and the conventional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolts" of the electorate and in the sudden reversal of the collective state of mind of recent times: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, through the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, to the rebellion of American MPs against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy also plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, its parties, its programs, but also its rites, magazines, intellectual believers, some would say their format, has more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value with regard to what is happening today in the lower social strata of the West, which is intensified by the financial crisis and driven to the point of oversizedness.
In view of all this, it would simply be an exaggeration to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The super glue that goes up on walls
To defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and be able to climb walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which now seems to be close to its goal.
Using an adhesive applied to an area of only 2.5 sq cm, the researchers succeeded in fixing a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO – an American journal, has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the adhesives already used, which use a special carbon structure called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of the glue can be thought of as a series of tubes arranged into a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered by microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
The tests carried out with various materials such as glass Teflon and sandpaper have shown that the new glue is ten times stronger than the holding capacity of the reptiles' feet and at the same time "easily removed from the wall," according to Liming Dai, a researcher in the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
WALKING ALONG WALLS? "This material could be used as an ephemeral adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
To walk up walls like Spiderman? Perhaps, but the researchers are thinking of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other areas of application could fall into the field of space travel.
So for now, the superheroes will have to wait.
THE OTHER KIND OF RESEARCH – the University of Berkeley, California, is also dedicated to a new type of glue.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, the Californian scientists present an adhesive made of microfibers that, like hair, clean themselves from dust by moving on a surface and thus always maintain perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed especially in summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, can cause serious damage to health if taken at the same time as certain essential medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of them by the body.
David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points out the risk of packaged as well as fresh fruit juices in connection with medication. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he sounded the alarm again: a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption capacity of certain essential drugs to such an extent that they are virtually eliminated and thus endangers the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, anti-asthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
DRUGS AT RISK – In a report two years ago, the same agency of the drug warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mix, stressing to pay attention to what is drunk in conjunction with drugs such as diazepan or metadon.
IT'S NOT JUST GRAPEFRUIT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually immediately forwarded to the various international manufacturers, who are so free to change consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the package leaflet and, if there are still uncertainties, not to be afraid to ask a pharmacist or doctor," emphasizes the expert of the Ansa agency.
Nobel Prize in Economics goes to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize in Economics is awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his analysis of trade patterns and the establishment of economic activities.
The 55-year-old Krugman is a neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is known for his regular articles for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration's economic and foreign policies.
A few months after the attacks of September 11, 2001, during the days of the Enron collapse, Krugman had claimed in a New York Times editorial that this second event was more decisive to US history than the attacks.
A prediction that received not a little polemic as an answer and was held against the economist years later, but today proves to be completely correct.
"I am surprised and also shocked at how quickly the memory of the scandals surrounding the collapses of Enron or Worldcom has disappeared from public view," Krugman said in late 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is an "economist of great value," but also a trivializer with a "very aggressive style, particularly directed against the excessive liberalism of the Bush administration."
Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package is released
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has arrived; As a free replacement for Microsoft's Office, the open source software is gaining an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the volunteer developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office now presents itself to the public with some novelties: in addition to a revised and now more spartan designed initial menu, a completely guaranteed compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS X is finally achieved, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format,  i.e. the latest standard ISO version.
Attention was also paid to compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes it easier to send via email, for example. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics editing modules and at the same time preserve the original appearance of the page.
"Hybrid" PDF files can now also be generated, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format by the elements of a table and a word processing system.
Collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited by multiple hands by different users, avoiding conflicts during changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a question in order to guarantee a better correction procedure.
Some companies are currently in the process of releasing various features of OpenOffice on the Internet (on the cloud), while the final result will be announced in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. Thus, it follows the English version, which is on the mirrors since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, you can have the installation CD sent to your home or office.
However, if the freedom from costs can be an incentive for the dissemination of the program in private households, it is also in the field of business, where OpenOffice could succeed in the big hit: after all, various institutions of public administration and schools have already switched to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of training, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word-corresponding text creation program; Calc, the spreadsheet program aimed at displacing Excel; Impress, for creating presentations as with PowerPoint; Dbase for running databases instead of the more well-known Access; and finally Draw, a graphics module.
The target for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a target that can easily be exceeded with 3 million and 600 thousand already reached.
Kohl also tested positive and thus the fourth doping case
A new doping case opens up in the context of the last Tour de France: it is the Austrian athlete Bernhard Kohl of the Gerolsteiner team, who is ranked third and winner of the jersey of the best climber.
The news was published by the daily newspaper L'Equipe on its website.
Team Gerolsteiner's 26-year-old Kohl is the fourth rider to test positive for Cera, the third-generation Epo. Previously, this was already the case with the Italians Riccardo Riccò and Leonardo Piepoli as well as the German Stefan Schumacher.
The analyses from Kohl's blood samples are among those carried out in recent weeks by the Losanna and Chatenay-Malabry laboratories.
