IMMIGRATION: THE NEW YORK TIMES ASKS: IS ITALY RACIST?
Italy, "the former country of emigrants, has recently become one of the preferred countries for immigrants", who are accepted only with reluctance.
Does this make the Belpaese a nation of racists? This is what the New York Times asks in a long article devoted entirely to the issue of racism in Italy, based on the case of the young Abdul William Guibre, a young Burkina Faso-born Abdul William Guibre, who was murdered in Milan a month ago after stealing a pack of biscuits.
The case testifies to what the Times calls the "paradox of the North": the northern regions are those with "the most integration and job opportunities" and yet "the highest levels of anti-immigration sentiment and support for the Northern League."
