Billionaire Steve Fossett's small plane that disappeared a year ago recovered
The small plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 on a flight over the Nevada desert, was found.
The individual parts were found on a high plateau of 3000 m altitude, in the area of the Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes between the states of California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains were found.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson completely dispelled the last doubts during a press conference: "The plane has been located, whereupon a force has been sent. Now we have the certainty that it is the plane Steve Fossett flew on on the day of his disappearance."
Mr. Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found on or near the plane.
The 63-year-old billionaire was pronounced dead in February.
The U.S. Bureau of Transportation Safety (Ntsb) announced that just a few hours after the sighting of the aircraft, a crew was sent to identify the aircraft: the Bellanca 8kcab, which was lost on September 3, 2007, after Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a 3-hour flight.
Yesterday, also in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal belongings were found by a couple near their home on the Mammoth Lakes.
These are two IDs bearing Fossett's name, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett had been abandoned a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history through a long succession of records.
In 2002, at the sixth attempt, he became the first person to circle the globe in a hot air balloon: a two-week, lonely flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world in a single non-stop flight.
Among his several records is also a high-altitude flight of 15445 m over the Andes, but this one with a co-pilot.
Glk, the advertisement you don't expect
An SUV that stands out from conventional schemes due to its original design and special lines, the sweeping surface and its clear angles.
Mercedes-Benz has tried to breathe new life into the sector with this off-roader.
Precisely because of its extraordinary characteristics, the presentation of the Suv Glk, which will be on display in the Mercedes-Benz showroom from 17 October, will also be unconventional.
Thus, the advertising drum that will accompany the appearance of the new model will also appear in a new guise, namely in the form of a 3D campaign – this is a novelty in the automotive sector in backward Italy.
A project with a maximum effort, which will be carried out in different phases that will occupy the central shopping street of Milan, Corso Como, until 15 November.
The first bevel will consist of the presentation of the car in shape, with 3D glasses distributed near Corso Como to give the whole a special look: the new SUV will thus appear in its almost real dimensions as a three-dimensional model.
In fact, the car will appear to emerge from the poster on which it is depicted.
With the help of Elumina8 technology, the new Glk is illuminated in all its details at different moments in order to reassemble itself as a whole.
Undoubtedly, it is the concern of Mercedes with this advertising to introduce a new type of car advertising into this rather stereotypical field.
But will it be possible to stimulate the interest of future buyers? We'll see.
Now it is clear who the Italian hooligans are
They come from the Triveneto – now they risk stadium ban
