Students victims of high rents of up to 900 euros per room
The market for student housing knows no crises.
According to the latest research by Sunia, the tenants' union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious features. In fact, crowds of students lose their right to study because their families are unable to support them at this level" – says Laura Mariani, head of the Sunia – "in these cities, the great demand from students leads to a deformation of the market, which has also harmed the other inhabitants.
In addition, most rental offers contain a number of violations: free contracts, lack of registrations, no rent limit, unauthorized subletting.
For Sunia, there is a need for extraordinary measures that lead to lower rental prices through a revision of the taxation.
A closer look at the study reveals that in Milan a place to sleep in the Brianza district requires about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends with 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera districts or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, a sleeping place costs an average of 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the districts around the university, 250/280 euros are needed for a place to sleep, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, prices in the districts around the university are around 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a place to sleep in a double room.
Only slightly lower are the rents in the districts around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who move to the outskirts can save money: 300 euros for a place to sleep and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a place to sleep, for a room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive districts, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, a sleeping place costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they have a greater weight in the urban economy.
In cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more common, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: rents that are 25-30% above the average are demanded by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas close due to the favoured multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture by director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-hall complexes in the periphery, in the long run means death for the single-hall cinema in the centre. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also bears the hallmarks of a cultural crime.
Mostly historical places full of memories are affected, "it's like losing a friend with whom you've covered a stretch of the road full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", which won him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak for themselves: in the last five years, the enormous number of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; this bill was largely paid by cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions that have registered the largest number of these modern cinemas: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy tops the lists, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way", says Paolo Protti, President of ANEC, "it is useful that new structures are also emerging, but the first priority is the preservation of what already exists, because if a hall in the city closes, not all its regular customers are willing to go to a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here remains the missing budget for the fund of the trade association outer eight: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from an ethical and moral standpoint that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be needed."
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city which, fearful of the old cinemas, decided to protect them by an agreement between the municipality and Anec; it is the first agreement of its kind in Italy aimed at protecting and supporting traditional cinemas, both in the historic centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are also tax advantages for cinema operators and advantages for the public in terms of public transport: it will be allowed to drive into the traffic-restricted areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking rates.
"It is a welcome initiative", says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will follow our example and also develop new concepts.
Certainly, however, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to do something against the superpower of multiplex halls, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important theme for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been toying with the idea for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years; when I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side so as not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was ready to adapt the decisions of the municipality to the interests of the mafia group Piromalli.
The accusations made by the legal profession of the anti-mafia authority of Calabria against the mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia business, are serious.
Also handcuffed were Gioacchino Piromalli, the older mediator between the clan and the public administration, and his nephew: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the boss of the clan, had already been convicted of involvement in criminal organizations of the mafia, at that time to a compensation sum of 10 million euros.
"Disregarding any kind of moral and legal norm," the lawyers write, "the two local administrations had decided to pay the lawyer Piromalli money for consulting services."
