When the energy comes from the waves, suddenly the big ones run up
It is a never-ending source of money that covers over 70% of the surface of the planet and only now do the world's major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at and trying to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; it is no coincidence that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of ocean energy was forgotten, but now environmental organizations and the rise in oil prices are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy needs could be met by the energy generated by ocean waves.
This would be twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be the currents and tides.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to bet on ocean energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy sector are now relying on marine energy generation.
"Chevron is investigating these technologies," a spokesman for a company known to the US giant told the Wall Street Journal, and is considering the possibility of working with us.
This involves obtaining approval from the US Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign that should not be underestimated, especially when you consider that oil continues to be produced by the USA in Alaska and that President Bush recently set plans for new wells in motion.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; Although the details are not known, observers speak of increasing interest.
Technologies still in need of improvement.
Experts speak of a technology that is still on the move, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as the one in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small scale and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, producing energy on a large scale requires technologies with a far greater impact on the environment.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater cables.
So far, there are four planned plants of this kind, which are just waiting for the state approval. Some of the energy generated could also be used for military installations.
Meanwhile, Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and a parking lot using submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotary movement.
According to Verdant, there is already a long line of potential clients waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Power Generation Research, the potential of the tides currently deserves special interest.
Although it is an irregular phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and waves, and are therefore a more trustworthy source of electricity.
It is precisely tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska as well as other coastal states to invest 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
